# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: self-driving-perception
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The scientific discipline of computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, multi-dimensional data from a 3D scanner, 3D point clouds from LiDaR sensors, or medical scanning devices.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The technological discipline of computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models to the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Subdisciplines of computer vision include scene reconstruction, object detection, event detection, activity recognition, video tracking, object recognition, 3D pose estimation, learning, indexing, motion estimation, visual servoing, 3D scene modeling, and image restoration.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Computer vision is an interdisciplinary field that deals with how computers can be made to gain high-level understanding from digital images or videos.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] From the perspective of engineering, it seeks to automate tasks that the human visual system can do.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] "Computer vision is concerned with the automatic extraction, analysis, and understanding of useful information from a single image or a sequence of images.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] It involves the development of a theoretical and algorithmic basis to achieve automatic visual understanding." As a scientific discipline, computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, or multi-dimensional data from a medical scanner.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] As a technological discipline, computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models for the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Machine vision refers to a systems engineering discipline, especially in the context of factory automation.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] In more recent times, the terms computer vision and machine vision have converged to a greater degree.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] In the late 1960s, computer vision began at universities that were pioneering artificial intelligence.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] It was meant to mimic the human visual system as a stepping stone to endowing robots with intelligent behavior.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] In 1966, it was believed that this could be achieved through an undergraduate summer project, by attaching a camera to a computer and having it "describe what it saw".
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] What distinguished computer vision from the prevalent field of digital image processing at that time was a desire to extract three-dimensional structure from images with the goal of achieving full scene understanding.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The next decade saw studies based on more rigorous mathematical analysis and quantitative aspects of computer vision.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] These include the concept of scale-space, the inference of shape from various cues such as shading, texture and focus, and contour models known as snakes.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Researchers also realized that many of these mathematical concepts could be treated within the same optimization framework as regularization and Markov random fields.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] By the 1990s, some of the previous research topics became more active than others.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Research in projective 3-D reconstructions led to better understanding of camera calibration.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] With the advent of optimization methods for camera calibration, it was realized that a lot of the ideas were already explored in bundle adjustment theory from the field of photogrammetry.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] This led to methods for sparse 3-D reconstructions of scenes from multiple images.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Progress was made on the dense stereo correspondence problem and further multi-view stereo techniques.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] At the same time, variations of graph cut were used to solve image segmentation.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] This decade also marked the first time statistical learning techniques were used in practice to recognize faces in images (see Eigenface).
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Toward the end of the 1990s, a significant change came about with the increased interaction between the fields of computer graphics and computer vision.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] This included image-based rendering, image morphing, view interpolation, panoramic image stitching and early light-field rendering.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Recent work has seen the resurgence of feature-based methods used in conjunction with machine learning techniques and complex optimization frameworks.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The advancement of Deep Learning techniques has brought further life to the field of computer vision.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The accuracy of deep learning algorithms on several benchmark computer vision data sets for tasks ranging from classification, segmentation and optical flow has surpassed prior methods.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Solid-state physics is another field that is closely related to computer vision.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems rely on image sensors, which detect electromagnetic radiation, which is typically in the form of either visible, infrared or ultraviolet light.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The sensors are designed using quantum physics.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The process by which light interacts with surfaces is explained using physics.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Physics explains the behavior of optics which are a core part of most imaging systems.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Sophisticated image sensors even require quantum mechanics to provide a complete understanding of the image formation process.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Also, various measurement problems in physics can be addressed using computer vision, for example, motion in fluids.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] However, the instance of a ring-textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] In addition, a shell that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Neurobiology has greatly influenced the development of computer vision algorithms.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Over the last century, there has been an extensive study of eyes, neurons, and brain structures devoted to the processing of visual stimuli in both humans and various animals.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] This has led to a coarse yet convoluted description of how natural vision systems operate in order to solve certain vision-related tasks.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] These results have led to a sub-field within computer vision where artificial systems are designed to mimic the processing and behavior of biological systems at different levels of complexity.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Also, some of the learning-based methods developed within computer vision (*e.g.* neural net and deep learning based image and feature analysis and classification) have their background in neurobiology.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The Neocognitron, a neural network developed in the 1970s by Kunihiko Fukushima, is an early example of computer vision taking direct inspiration from neurobiology, specifically the primary visual cortex.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Some strands of computer vision research are closely related to the study of biological vision—indeed, just as many strands of AI research are closely tied with research into human intelligence and the use of stored knowledge to interpret, integrate, and utilize visual information.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The field of biological vision studies and models the physiological processes behind visual perception in humans and other animals.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Computer vision, on the other hand, develops and describes the algorithms implemented in software and hardware behind artificial vision systems.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] An interdisciplinary exchange between biological and computer vision has proven fruitful for both fields.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Yet another field related to computer vision is signal processing.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Many methods for processing one-variable signals, typically temporal signals, can be extended in a natural way to the processing of two-variable signals or multi-variable signals in computer vision.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] However, because of the specific nature of images, there are many methods developed within computer vision that have no counterpart in the processing of one-variable signals.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Together with the multi-dimensionality of the signal, this defines a subfield in signal processing as a part of computer vision.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Robot navigation sometimes deals with autonomous path planning or deliberation for robotic systems to navigate through an environment.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] A detailed understanding of these environments is required to navigate through them.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Visual computing is a generic term for all computer science disciplines dealing with images and 3D models, such as computer graphics, image processing, visualization, computer vision, virtual and augmented reality, video processing, and computational visualistics.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes aspects of pattern recognition, human computer interaction, machine learning and digital libraries.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The core challenges are the acquisition, processing, analysis and rendering of visual information (mainly images and video).
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Application areas include industrial quality control, medical image processing and visualization, surveying, robotics, multimedia systems, virtual heritage, special effects in movies and television, and ludology.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes digital art and digital media studies.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Besides the above-mentioned views on computer vision, many of the related research topics can also be studied from a purely mathematical point of view.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] For example, many methods in computer vision are based on statistics, optimization or geometry.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Finally, a significant part of the field is devoted to the implementation aspect of computer vision; how existing methods can be realized in various combinations of software and hardware, or how these methods can be modified in order to gain processing speed without losing too much performance.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Computer vision is also used in fashion eCommerce, inventory management, patent search, furniture, and the beauty industry.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The fields most closely related to computer vision are image processing, image analysis and machine vision.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] There is a significant overlap in the range of techniques and applications that these cover.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] This implies that the basic techniques that are used and developed in these fields are similar, something which can be interpreted as there is only one field with different names.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] In image processing, the input and output are both images, whereas in computer vision, the input is an image or video, and the output could be an enhanced image, an analysis of the image's content, or even a system's behavior based on that analysis.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Computer graphics produces image data from 3D models, and computer vision often produces 3D models from image data.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] There is also a trend towards a combination of the two disciplines, *e.g.*, as explored in augmented reality.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Photogrammetry also overlaps with computer vision, e.g., stereophotogrammetry vs. computer stereo vision.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Applications range from tasks such as industrial machine vision systems which, say, inspect bottles speeding by on a production line, to research into artificial intelligence and computers or robots that can comprehend the world around them.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The computer vision and machine vision fields have significant overlap.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Computer vision covers the core technology of automated image analysis which is used in many fields.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Machine vision usually refers to a process of combining automated image analysis with other methods and technologies to provide automated inspection and robot guidance in industrial applications.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] In many computer-vision applications, computers are pre-programmed to solve a particular task, but methods based on learning are now becoming increasingly common.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] For 2024, the leading areas of computer vision were industry (market size US$5.22 billion), medicine (market size US$2.6 billion), military (market size US$996.2 million).
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] One of the most prominent application fields is medical computer vision, or medical image processing, characterized by the extraction of information from image data to diagnose a patient.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] An example of this is the detection of tumours, arteriosclerosis or other malign changes, and a variety of dental pathologies; measurements of organ dimensions, blood flow, etc. are another example.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] It also supports medical research by providing new information: *e.g.*, about the structure of the brain or the quality of medical treatments.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Applications of computer vision in the medical area also include enhancement of images interpreted by humans—ultrasonic images or X-ray images, for example—to reduce the influence of noise.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] A second application area in computer vision is in industry, sometimes called machine vision, where information is extracted for the purpose of supporting a production process.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] One example is quality control where details or final products are being automatically inspected in order to find defects.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] One of the most prevalent fields for such inspecti is the Wafer industry in which every single Wafer is being measured and inspected for inaccuracies or defects to prevent a computer chip from coming to market in an unusable manner.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Another example is a measurement of the position and orientation of details to be picked up by a robot arm.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Machine vision is also heavily used in the agricultural processes to remove undesirable foodstuff from bulk material, a process called optical sorting.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The obvious examples are the detection of enemy soldiers or vehicles and missile guidance.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] More advanced systems for missile guidance send the missile to an area rather than a specific target, and target selection is made when the missile reaches the area based on locally acquired image data.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Modern military concepts, such as "battlefield awareness", imply that various sensors, including image sensors, provide a rich set of information about a combat scene that can be used to support strategic decisions.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] In this case, automatic processing of the data is used to reduce complexity and to fuse information from multiple sensors to increase reliability.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] One of the newer application areas is autonomous vehicles, which include submersibles, land-based vehicles (small robots with wheels, cars, or trucks), aerial vehicles, and unmanned aerial vehicles (UAV).
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The level of autonomy ranges from fully autonomous (unmanned) vehicles to vehicles where computer-vision-based systems support a driver or a pilot in various situations.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Fully autonomous vehicles typically use computer vision for navigation, e.g., for knowing where they are or mapping their environment (SLAM), for detecting obstacles.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] It can also be used for detecting certain task-specific events, *e.g.*, a UAV looking for forest fires.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Examples of supporting systems are obstacle warning systems in cars, cameras and LiDAR sensors in vehicles, and systems for autonomous landing of aircraft.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Several car manufacturers have demonstrated systems for autonomous driving of cars.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] There are ample examples of military autonomous vehicles ranging from advanced missiles to UAVs for recon missions or missile guidance.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Space exploration is already being made with autonomous vehicles using computer vision, *e.g.*, NASA's *Curiosity* and CNSA's *Yutu-2* rover.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Materials such as rubber and silicon are being used to create sensors that allow for applications such as detecting microundulations and calibrating robotic hands.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Rubber can be used in order to create a mold that can be placed over a finger, inside of this mold would be multiple strain gauges.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The finger mold and sensors could then be placed on top of a small sheet of rubber containing an array of rubber pins.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] A user can then wear the finger mold and trace a surface.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] A computer can then read the data from the strain gauges and measure if one or more of the pins are being pushed upward.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] If a pin is being pushed upward then the computer can recognize this as an imperfection in the surface.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] This sort of technology is useful in order to receive accurate data on imperfections on a very large surface.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Another variation of this finger mold sensor are sensors that contain a camera suspended in silicon.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The silicon forms a dome around the outside of the camera and embedded in the silicon are point markers that are equally spaced.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] These cameras can then be placed on devices such as robotic hands in order to allow the computer to receive highly accurate tactile data.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Each of the application areas described above employ a range of computer vision tasks; more or less well-defined measurement problems or processing problems, which can be solved using a variety of methods.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Some examples of typical computer vision tasks are presented below.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Computer vision tasks include methods for acquiring, processing, analyzing and understanding digital images, and extraction of high-dimensional data from the real world in order to produce numerical or symbolic information, *e.g.*, in the forms of decisions.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Understanding in this context means the transformation of visual images into descriptions of the world that can interface with other thought processes and elicit appropriate action.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] This image understanding can be seen as the disentangling of symbolic information from image data using models constructed with the aid of geometry, physics, statistics, and learning theory.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The classical problem in computer vision, image processing, and machine vision is that of determining whether or not the image data contains some specific object, feature, or activity.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Different varieties of recognition problem are described in the literature.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Currently, the best algorithms for such tasks are based on convolutional neural networks.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] An illustration of their capabilities is given by the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge; this is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and 1000 object classes used in the competition.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests is now close to that of humans.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on the stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters (an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras).
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] By contrast, those kinds of images rarely trouble humans.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Humans, however, tend to have trouble with other issues.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained classes, such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this with ease.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Several tasks relate to motion estimation, where an image sequence is processed to produce an estimate of the velocity either at each points in the image or in the 3D scene or even of the camera that produces the images.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Given one or (typically) more images of a scene, or a video, scene reconstruction aims at computing a 3D model of the scene.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] In the simplest case, the model can be a set of 3D points.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods produce a complete 3D surface model.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The advent of 3D imaging not requiring motion or scanning, and related processing algorithms is enabling rapid advances in this field.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Grid-based 3D sensing can be used to acquire 3D images from multiple angles.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Algorithms are now available to stitch multiple 3D images together into point clouds and 3D models.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Image restoration comes into the picture when the original image is degraded or damaged due to some external factors like lens wrong positioning, transmission interference, low lighting or motion blurs, etc., which is referred to as noise.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] When the images are degraded or damaged, the information to be extracted from them also gets damaged.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Therefore, we need to recover or restore the image as it was intended to be.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The aim of image restoration is the removal of noise (sensor noise, motion blur, etc.) from images.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The simplest possible approach for noise removal is various types of filters, such as low-pass filters or median filters.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods assume a model of how the local image structures look to distinguish them from noise.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] By first analyzing the image data in terms of the local image structures, such as lines or edges, and then controlling the filtering based on local information from the analysis step, a better level of noise removal is usually obtained compared to the simpler approaches.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The organization of a computer vision system is highly application-dependent.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Some systems are stand-alone applications that solve a specific measurement or detection problem, while others constitute a sub-system of a larger design which, for example, also contains sub-systems for control of mechanical actuators, planning, information databases, man-machine interfaces, etc.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The specific implementation of a computer vision system also depends on whether its functionality is pre-specified or if some part of it can be learned or modified during operation.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Many functions are unique to the application.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] There are, however, typical functions that are found in many computer vision systems.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] More complex features may be related to texture, shape, or motion.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Image-understanding systems (IUS) include three levels of abstraction as follows: low level includes image primitives such as edges, texture elements, or regions; intermediate level includes boundaries, surfaces and volumes; and high level includes objects, scenes, or events.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Many of these requirements are entirely topics for further research.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] The representational requirements in the designing of IUS for these levels are: representation of prototypical concepts, concept organization, spatial knowledge, temporal knowledge, scaling, and description by comparison and differentiation.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] While inference refers to the process of deriving new, not explicitly represented facts from currently known facts, control refers to the process that selects which of the many inference, search, and matching techniques should be applied at a particular stage of processing.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Inference and control requirements for IUS are: search and hypothesis activation, matching and hypothesis testing, generation and use of expectations, change and focus of attention, certainty and strength of belief, inference and goal satisfaction.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] There are many kinds of computer vision systems; however, all of them contain these basic elements: a power source, at least one image acquisition device (camera, ccd, etc.), a processor, and control and communication cables or some kind of wireless interconnection mechanism.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] In addition, a practical vision system contains software, as well as a display in order to monitor the system.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Vision systems for inner spaces, as most industrial ones, contain an illumination system and may be placed in a controlled environment.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Furthermore, a completed system includes many accessories, such as camera supports, cables, and connectors.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems use visible-light cameras passively viewing a scene at frame rates of at most 60 frames per second (usually far slower).
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Such hardware captures "images" that are then processed often using the same computer vision algorithms used to process visible-light images.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] For applications in robotics, fast, real-time video systems are critically important and often can simplify the processing needed for certain algorithms.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] When combined with a high-speed projector, fast image acquisition allows 3D measurement and feature tracking to be realized.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] Egocentric vision systems are composed of a wearable camera that automatically take pictures from a first-person perspective.
[src:self-driving-perception/computer-vision] As of 2016, vision processing units are emerging as a new class of processors to complement CPUs and graphics processing units (GPUs) in this role.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Depth perception arises from a variety of depth cues.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] These are typically classified into binocular cues and monocular cues.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Binocular cues are based on the receipt of sensory information in three dimensions by both eyes while monocular cues can be observed with just one eye.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Binocular cues include retinal disparity, which exploits parallax and vergence.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Stereopsis is made possible with binocular vision.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Monocular cues include relative size (distant objects subtend smaller visual angles than near objects), texture gradient, occlusion, linear perspective, contrast differences, and motion parallax.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Monocular cues provide depth information even when viewing a scene with only one eye.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] When an observer moves, the apparent relative motion of several stationary objects against a background gives hints about their relative distance.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] If information about the direction and velocity of movement is known, motion parallax can provide absolute depth information.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] This effect can be seen clearly when riding in a car.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Nearby things pass quickly, while far-off objects appear stationary.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] When an object moves toward the observer, the retinal projection of an object expands over a period of time, which leads to the perception of movement in a line toward the observer.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Another name for this phenomenon is *depth from optical expansion*.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The dynamic stimulus change enables the observer not only to see the object as moving, but to perceive the distance of the moving object.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Thus, in this context, the changing size serves as a distance cue.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] A related phenomenon is the visual system's capacity to calculate time-to-contact (TTC) of an approaching object from the rate of optical expansion – a useful ability in contexts ranging from driving a car to playing a ball game.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] However, the calculation of TTC is, strictly speaking, a perception of velocity rather than depth.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] If a stationary rigid figure (for example, a wire cube) is placed in front of a point source of light so that its shadow falls on a translucent screen, an observer on the other side of the screen will see a two-dimensional pattern of lines.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] But if the cube rotates, the visual system will extract the necessary information for perception of the third dimension from the movements of the lines, and a cube is seen.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] This is an example of the *kinetic depth effect*.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The effect also occurs when the rotating object is solid (rather than an outline figure), provided that the projected shadow consists of lines which have definite corners or end points, and that these lines change in both length and orientation during the rotation.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The property of parallel lines converging in the distance, at infinity, allows us to reconstruct the relative distance of two parts of an object, or of landscape features.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] An example would be standing on a straight road, looking down the road, and noticing the road narrows as it goes off in the distance.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Visual perception of perspective in real space, for instance in rooms, in settlements and in nature, is a result of several optical impressions and the interpretation by the visual system.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The angle of vision is important for the apparent size.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] A nearby object is imaged on a larger area on the retina, while the same object or an object of the same size further away is imaged on a smaller area.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The perception of perspective is possible when looking with one eye only, but stereoscopic vision enhances the impression of the spatial.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Regardless of whether the light rays entering the eye come from a three-dimensional space or from a two-dimensional image, they hit the inside of the eye on the retina as a surface.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] What a person sees, is based on the reconstruction by their visual system, in which one and the same image on the retina can be interpreted both two-dimensionally and three-dimensionally.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] If a three-dimensional interpretation has been recognised, it receives a preference and determines the perception.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] In spatial vision, the horizontal line of sight can play a role.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] In the picture taken from the window of a house, the horizontal line of sight is at the level of the second floor (yellow line).
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Below this line, the further away objects are, the higher up in the visual field they appear.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Above the horizontal line of sight, objects that are further away appear lower than those that are closer.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] To represent spatial impressions in graphical perspective, one can use a vanishing point.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] When looking at long geographical distances, perspective effects also partially result from the angle of vision, but not only by this.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] In picture 5 of the series, in the background is Mont Blanc, the highest mountain in the Alps.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] It appears lower than the mountain in front in the center of the picture.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Measurements and calculations can be used to determine the proportion of the curvature of Earth in the subjectively perceived proportions.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] If two objects are known to be the same size (for example, two trees) but their absolute size is unknown, relative size cues can provide information about the relative depth of the two objects.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] If one subtends a larger visual angle on the retina than the other, the object which subtends the larger visual angle appears closer.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Since the visual angle of an object projected onto the retina decreases with distance, this information can be combined with previous knowledge of the object's size to determine the absolute depth of the object.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] For example, people are generally familiar with the size of an average automobile.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] This prior knowledge can be combined with information about the angle it subtends on the retina to determine the absolute depth of an automobile in a scene.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Even if the actual size of the object is unknown and there is only one object visible, a smaller object seems farther away than a large object that is presented at the same location.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Due to light scattering by the atmosphere, objects that are a great distance away have lower luminance contrast and lower color saturation.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Due to this, images seem hazy the farther they are away from a person's point of view.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] In computer graphics, this is often called "distance fog".
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The foreground has high contrast; the background has low contrast.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Objects differing only in their contrast with a background appear to be at different depths.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The color of distant objects is also shifted toward the blue end of the spectrum (for example, distant mountains).
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Some painters, notably Cézanne, employ "warm" pigments (red, yellow and orange) to bring features forward towards the viewer, and "cool" ones (blue, violet, and blue-green) to indicate the part of a form that curves away from the picture plane.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Accommodation is an oculomotor cue for depth perception.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] When humans try to focus on distant objects, the ciliary muscles relax, allowing the eye lens to become thinner, which increases the focal length.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Depth perception of distant objects is made possible by other methods besides accommodation.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The kinesthetic sensations of the contracting and relaxing ciliary muscles (intraocular muscles) are sent to the visual cortex where they are used for interpreting distance and depth.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Accommodation is only effective for distances less than 2 meters.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Occultation (also referred to as *interposition*) happens when near surfaces overlap far surfaces.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] If one object partially blocks the view of another object, humans perceive it as closer.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] However, this information only allows the observer to make a "ranking" of relative nearness.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The presence of monocular ambient occlusions consist of the object's texture and geometry.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] These phenomena are able to reduce depth perception latency both in natural and artificial stimuli.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] At the outer extremes of the visual field, parallel lines become curved, as in a photo taken through a fisheye lens.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] This effect, although it is usually eliminated from both art and photos by the cropping or framing of a picture, greatly enhances the viewer's sense of being positioned within a real, three-dimensional space.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Fine details on nearby objects can be seen clearly, whereas such details are not visible on faraway objects.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Texture gradients are the grains of an item.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] For example, on a long gravel road, the gravel near the observer can be clearly seen of shape, size and colour.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] In the distance, the road's texture cannot be clearly differentiated.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The way that light falls on an object and reflects off its surfaces, and the shadows that are cast by objects provide an effective cue for the brain to determine the shape of objects and their position in space.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Selective image blurring is very commonly used in photography and video to establish the impression of depth.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] This can act as a monocular cue even when all other cues are removed.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] It may contribute to depth perception in natural retinal images, because the depth of focus of the human eye is limited.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] In addition, there are several depth estimation algorithms based on defocus and blurring.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Some jumping spiders are known to use image defocus to judge depth.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] When an object is visible relative to the horizon, humans tend to perceive objects which are closer to the horizon as being farther away from them, and objects which are farther from the horizon as being closer to them.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] In addition, if an object moves from a position close to the horizon to a position higher or lower than the horizon, it will appear to move closer to the viewer.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Ocular parallax is a perceptual effect where the rotation of the eye causes perspective-dependent image shifts.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] This happens because the optical center and the rotation center of the eye are not the same.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Ocular parallax does not require head movement.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] It is separate and distinct from motion parallax.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Binocular cues provide depth information when viewing a scene with both eyes.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Animals that have their eyes placed frontally can also use information derived from the different projections of objects onto each retina to judge depth.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] By using two images of the same scene obtained from slightly different angles, it is possible to triangulate the distance to an object with a high degree of accuracy.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Each eye views a slightly different angle of an object seen by the left and right eyes.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] This happens because of the horizontal separation parallax of the eyes.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] If an object is far away, the disparity of that image falling on both retinas will be small.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] If the object is close or near, the disparity will be large.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] It is stereopsis that tricks people into thinking they perceive depth when viewing Magic Eyes, autostereograms, 3D movies, and stereoscopic photos.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Convergence is a binocular oculomotor cue for distance and depth perception.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Because of stereopsis, the two eyeballs focus on the same object; in doing so they converge.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The convergence will stretch the extraocular muscles – the receptors for this are muscle spindles.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] As happens with the monocular accommodation cue, kinesthetic sensations from these extraocular muscles also help in distance and depth perception.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The angle of convergence is smaller when the eye is fixating on objects which are far away.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Convergence is effective for distances less than 10 meters.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Antonio Medina Puerta demonstrated that retinal images with no parallax disparity but with different shadows were fused stereoscopically, imparting depth perception to the imaged scene.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] He named the phenomenon "shadow stereopsis".
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Shadows are therefore an important, stereoscopic cue for depth perception.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Of these various cues, only convergence, accommodation and familiar size provide absolute distance information.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] All other cues are relative (as in, they can only be used to tell which objects are closer relative to others).
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Isaac Newton proposed that the optic nerve of humans and other primates has a specific architecture on its way from the eye to the brain.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Nearly half of the fibres from the human retina project to the brain hemisphere on the same side as the eye from which they originate.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] That architecture is labelled hemi-decussation or ipsilateral (same sided) visual projections (IVP).
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] In most other animals, these nerve fibres cross to the opposite side of the brain.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Bernhard von Gudden showed that the OC contains both crossed and uncrossed retinal fibers, and Ramon y Cajal observed that the grade of hemidecussation differs between species.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Gordon Lynn Walls formalized a commonly accepted notion into the law of Newton–Müller–Gudden (NGM) saying: that the degree of optic fibre decussation in the optic chiasm is contrariwise related to the degree of frontal orientation of the optical axes of the eyes.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] In other words, that the number of fibers that do not cross the midline is proportional to the size of the binocular visual field.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] However, an issue of the Newton–Müller–Gudden law is the considerable interspecific variation in IVP seen in non-mammalian species.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] That variation is unrelated to mode of life, taxonomic situation, and the overlap of visual fields.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The eye-forelimb (EF) hypothesis suggests that the need for accurate eye-hand control was key in the evolution of stereopsis.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The EF hypothesis postulates that it has a selective value to have short neural pathways between areas of the brain that receive visual information about the hand and the motor nuclei that control the coordination of the hand.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The essence of the EF hypothesis is that evolutionary transformation in OC will affect the length and thereby speed of these neural pathways.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The reverse is true for the left hand, the processing of visual, tactile information, and motor command – all of which takes place in the right hemisphere.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Cats and arboreal (tree-climbing) marsupials have analogous arrangements (between 30 and 45% of IVP and forward-directed eyes).
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The result will be that visual info of their forelimbs reaches the proper (executing) hemisphere.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The evolution has resulted in small, and gradual fluctuations in the direction of the nerve pathways in the OC.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] This transformation can go in either direction.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Snakes, cyclostomes and other animals that lack extremities have relatively many IVP.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Notably these animals have no limbs (hands, paws, fins or wings) to direct.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Besides, the left and right body parts of snakelike animals cannot move independently of each other.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] For example, if a snake coils clockwise, its left eye only sees the left body-part and in an anticlockwise position the same eye will see just the right body-part.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] For that reason, it is functional for snakes to have some IVP in the OC (Naked).
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Cyclostome descendants (in other words, most vertebrates) that due to evolution ceased to curl and, instead developed forelimbs would be favored by achieving completely crossed pathways as long as forelimbs were primarily occupied in a lateral direction.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Reptiles such as snakes that lost their limbs, would gain by recollecting a cluster of uncrossed fibres in their evolution.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] That seems to have happened, providing further support for the EF hypothesis.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Mice' paws are usually busy only in the lateral visual fields.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] So, it is in accordance with the EF hypothesis that mice have laterally situated eyes and very few crossings in the OC.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The list from the animal kingdom supporting the EF hypothesis is long (BBE).
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The EF hypothesis applies to essentially all vertebrates while the NGM law and stereopsis hypothesis largely apply just to mammals.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Even some mammals display important exceptions, e.g. dolphins have only uncrossed pathways although they are predators.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] It is a common suggestion that predatory animals generally have frontally-placed eyes since that permit them to evaluate the distance to prey, whereas preyed-upon animals have eyes in a lateral position, since that permit them to scan and detect the enemy in time.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] However, many predatory animals may also become prey, and several predators, for instance, the crocodile, have laterally situated eyes and no IVP at all.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] That OC architecture will provide short nerve connections and optimal eye control of the crocodile's front foot.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Birds, usually have laterally situated eyes, in spite of that they manage to fly through e.g. a dense wood.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Most open-plain herbivores, especially hoofed grazers, lack binocular vision because they have their eyes on the sides of the head, providing a panoramic, almost 360°, view of the horizon – enabling them to notice the approach of predators from almost any direction.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] However, most predators have both eyes looking forwards, allowing binocular depth perception and helping them to judge distances when they pounce or swoop down onto their prey.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Animals that spend a lot of time in trees take advantage of binocular vision in order to accurately judge distances when rapidly moving from branch to branch.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Matt Cartmill, a physical anthropologist and anatomist at Boston University, has criticized this theory, citing other arboreal species which lack binocular vision, such as squirrels and certain birds.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Instead, he proposes a "Visual Predation Hypothesis," which argues that ancestral primates were insectivorous predators resembling tarsiers, subject to the same selection pressure for frontal vision as other predatory species.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] He also uses this hypothesis to account for the specialization of primate hands, which he suggests became adapted for grasping prey, somewhat like the way raptors employ their talons.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Photographs capturing perspective are two-dimensional images that often illustrate the illusion of depth.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Photography utilizes size, environmental context, lighting, textural gradient, and other effects to capture the illusion of depth.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Stereoscopes and Viewmasters, as well as 3D films, employ binocular vision by forcing the viewer to see two images created from slightly different positions (points of view).
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Charles Wheatstone was the first to discuss depth perception being a cue of binocular disparity.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] He invented the stereoscope, which is an instrument with two eyepieces that displays two photographs of the same location/scene taken at relatively different angles.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] When observed, separately by each eye, the pairs of images induced a clear sense of depth.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] By contrast, a telephoto lens—used in televised sports, for example, to zero in on members of a stadium audience—has the opposite effect.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The viewer sees the size and detail of the scene as if it were close enough to touch, but the camera's perspective is still derived from its actual position a hundred meters away, so background faces and objects appear about the same size as those in the foreground.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Trained artists are keenly aware of the various methods for indicating spatial depth (color shading, distance fog, perspective and relative size), and take advantage of them to make their works appear "real".
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The viewer feels it would be possible to reach in and grab the nose of a Rembrandt portrait or an apple in a Cézanne still life—or step inside a landscape and walk around among its trees and rocks.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Cubism was based on the idea of incorporating multiple points of view in a painted image, as if to simulate the visual experience of being physically in the presence of the subject, and seeing it from different angles.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The radical experiments of Georges Braque, Pablo Picasso, Jean Metzinger's *Nu à la cheminée*, Albert Gleizes's *La Femme aux Phlox*, or Robert Delaunay's views of the Eiffel Tower, employ the explosive angularity of Cubism to exaggerate the traditional illusion of three-dimensional space.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] The subtle use of multiple points of view can be found in the pioneering late work of Cézanne, which both anticipated and inspired the first actual Cubists.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Cézanne's landscapes and still lives powerfully suggest the artist's own highly developed depth perception.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] Cubism, and indeed most of modern art is an attempt to confront, if not resolve, the paradox of suggesting spatial depth on a flat surface, and explore that inherent contradiction through innovative ways of seeing, as well as new methods of drawing and painting.
[src:self-driving-perception/depth-perception] In robotics and computer vision, depth perception is often achieved using sensors such as RGBD cameras.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] In this view, the viewer flies down to the rainforest canopy and flies through the virtual leaves.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] This visualisation shows an airplane collecting a 50 km swathe of lidar data over the Brazilian rainforest.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] For ground-level features, colours range from deep brown to tan.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Vegetation heights are depicted in shades of green, where dark greens are closest to the ground and light greens are the highest.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Lidar has terrestrial, airborne, and mobile uses.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] It is commonly used to make high-resolution maps, with applications in surveying, geodesy, geomatics, archaeology, geography, geology, geomorphology, seismology, forestry, atmospheric physics, laser guidance, airborne laser swathe mapping (ALSM), and laser altimetry.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] It is used to make digital 3-D representations of areas on the Earth's surface and ocean bottom of the intertidal and near coastal zone by varying the wavelength of light.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] It has also been increasingly used in control and navigation for autonomous cars and for the helicopter *Ingenuity* on its record-setting flights over the terrain of Mars.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Lidar has since been used extensively for atmospheric research and meteorology.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Lidar instruments fitted to aircraft and satellites carry out surveying and mapping – a recent example being the U.S.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Geological Survey Experimental Advanced Airborne Research Lidar.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] NASA has identified lidar as a key technology for enabling autonomous precision safe landing of future robotic and crewed lunar-landing vehicles.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The essential concept of lidar was originated by E.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Synge in 1930, who envisaged the use of powerful searchlights to probe the atmosphere.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Under the direction of Malcolm Stitch, the Hughes Aircraft Company introduced the first lidar-like system in 1961, shortly after the invention of the laser.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Intended for satellite tracking, this system combined laser-focused imaging with the ability to calculate distances by measuring the time for a signal to return using appropriate sensors and data acquisition electronics.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] It was originally called "Colidar" an acronym for "coherent light detecting and ranging", derived from the term "radar", itself an acronym for "radio detection and ranging".
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] All laser rangefinders, laser altimeters and lidar units are derived from the early colidar systems.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The first practical terrestrial application of a colidar system was the "Colidar Mark II", a large rifle-like laser rangefinder produced in 1963, which had a range of 11 km and an accuracy of 4.5 m, to be used for military targeting.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The first mention of lidar as a stand-alone word in 1963 suggests that it originated as a portmanteau of "light" and "radar": "Eventually the laser may provide an extremely sensitive detector of particular wavelengths from distant objects.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Meanwhile, it is being used to study the Moon by 'lidar' (light radar) ..." The name "photonic radar" is sometimes used to mean visible-spectrum range finding like lidar.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Lidar's first applications were in meteorology, for which the National Center for Atmospheric Research used it to measure clouds and pollution.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The general public became aware of the accuracy and usefulness of lidar systems in 1971 during the Apollo 15 mission, when astronauts used a laser altimeter to map the surface of the Moon.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Although the English language no longer treats "radar" as an acronym, (i.e., uncapitalized), the word "lidar" was capitalized as "LIDAR" or "LiDAR" in some publications beginning in the 1980s.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Various publications refer to lidar as "LIDAR", "LiDAR", "LIDaR", or "Lidar".
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The USGS uses both "LIDAR" and "lidar", sometimes in the same document; the *New York Times* predominantly uses "lidar" for staff-written articles, although contributing news feeds such as Reuters may use Lidar.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Lidar uses ultraviolet, visible, or near infrared light to image objects.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] It can target a wide range of materials, including non-metallic objects, rocks, rain, chemical compounds, aerosols, clouds and even single molecules.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] A narrow laser beam can map physical features with very high resolutions; for example, an aircraft can map terrain at 30-centimetre (12 in) resolution or better.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Wavelengths vary to suit the target: from about 10 micrometers (infrared) to approximately 250 nanometers (ultraviolet).
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Typically, light is reflected via backscattering, as opposed to pure reflection one might find with a mirror.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Different types of scattering are used for different lidar applications: most commonly Rayleigh scattering, Mie scattering, Raman scattering, and fluorescence.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Suitable combinations of wavelengths can allow remote mapping of atmospheric contents by identifying wavelength-dependent changes in the intensity of the returned signal.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The name "photonic radar" is sometimes used to mean visible-spectrum range finding like lidar, although photonic radar more strictly refers to radio-frequency range finding using photonics components.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] where *c* is the speed of light, *d* is the distance between the detector and the object or surface being detected, and *t* is the time spent for the laser light to travel to the object or surface being detected, then travel back to the detector.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The two kinds of lidar detection schemes are "incoherent" or direct energy detection (which principally measures amplitude changes of the reflected light) and coherent detection (best for measuring Doppler shifts, or changes in the phase of the reflected light).
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Coherent systems generally use optical heterodyne detection.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] This is more sensitive than direct detection and allows them to operate at much lower power, but requires more complex transceivers.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Both types employ pulse models: either *micropulse* or *high energy*.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Micropulse systems utilize intermittent bursts of energy.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] They developed as a result of ever-increasing computer power, combined with advances in laser technology.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] They use considerably less energy in the laser, typically on the order of one microjoule, and are often "eye-safe", meaning they can be used without safety precautions.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] 600–1,000 nm lasers are most common for non-scientific applications.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The maximum power of the laser is limited, or an automatic shut-off system which turns the laser off at specific altitudes is used in order to make it eye-safe for the people on the ground.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] One common alternative, 1,550 nm lasers, are eye-safe at relatively high power levels since this wavelength is strongly absorbed by water and barely reaches the retina, though camera sensors can still get damaged.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] A trade-off though is that current detector technology is less advanced, so these wavelengths are generally used at longer ranges with lower accuracies.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] They are also used for military applications because 1,550 nm is not visible in night vision goggles, unlike the shorter 1,000 nm infrared laser.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Airborne topographic mapping lidars generally use 1,064 nm diode-pumped YAG lasers, while bathymetric (underwater depth research) systems generally use 532 nm frequency-doubled diode pumped YAG lasers because 532 nm penetrates water with much less attenuation than 1,064 nm.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Laser settings include the laser repetition rate (which controls the data collection speed).
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Pulse length is generally an attribute of the laser cavity length, the number of passes required through the gain material (YAG, YLF, etc.), and Q-switch (pulsing) speed.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Better target resolution is achieved with shorter pulses, provided the lidar receiver detectors and electronics have sufficient bandwidth.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] A phased array can illuminate any direction by using a microscopic array of individual antennas.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Controlling the timing (phase) of each antenna steers a cohesive signal in a specific direction.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Phased arrays have been used in radar since the 1940s.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] On the order of a million optical antennas are used to see a radiation pattern of a certain size in a certain direction.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] To achieve this the phase of each individual antenna (emitter) are precisely controlled.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] It is very difficult, if possible at all, to use the same technique in a lidar.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The main problems are that all individual emitters must be coherent (technically coming from the same "master" oscillator or laser source), have dimensions about the wavelength of the emitted light (1 micron range) to act as a point source with their phases being controlled with high accuracy.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Microelectromechanical mirrors (MEMS) are not entirely solid-state.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] However, their tiny form factor provides many of the same cost benefits.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] A single laser is directed to a single mirror that can be reoriented to view any part of the target field.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] However, MEMS systems generally operate in a single plane (left to right).
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] To add a second dimension generally requires a second mirror that moves up and down.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Alternatively, another laser can hit the same mirror from another angle.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] MEMS systems can be disrupted by shock/vibration and may require repeated calibration.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Image development speed is affected by the speed at which they are scanned.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Options to scan the azimuth and elevation include dual oscillating plane mirrors, a combination with a polygon mirror, and a dual axis scanner.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Optic choices affect the angular resolution and range that can be detected.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] A hole mirror or a beam splitter are options to collect a return signal.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Two main photodetector technologies are used in lidar: solid-state photodetectors, such as silicon avalanche photodiodes, or photomultipliers.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The sensitivity of the receiver is another parameter that has to be balanced in a lidar design.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Lidar sensors mounted on mobile platforms such as airplanes or satellites require instrumentation to determine the absolute position and orientation of the sensor.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Such devices generally include a Global Positioning System receiver and an inertial measurement unit (IMU).
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Lidar uses active sensors that supply their own illumination source.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The energy source hits objects and the reflected energy is detected and measured by sensors.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Distance to the object is determined by recording the time between transmitted and backscattered pulses and by using the speed of light to calculate the distance traveled.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Flash lidar allows for 3-D imaging because of the camera's ability to emit a larger flash and sense the spatial relationships and dimensions of area of interest with the returned energy.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] This allows for more accurate imaging because the captured frames do not need to be stitched together, and the system is not sensitive to platform motion.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] 3-D imaging can be achieved using both scanning and non-scanning systems.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] "3-D gated viewing laser radar" is a non-scanning laser ranging system that applies a pulsed laser and a fast gated camera.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Research has begun for virtual beam steering using digital light processing (DLP) technology.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Imaging lidar can also be performed using arrays of high speed detectors and modulation sensitive detector arrays typically built on single chips using complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) and hybrid CMOS/charge-coupled device (CCD) fabrication techniques.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] In these devices each pixel performs some local processing such as demodulation or gating at high speed, downconverting the signals to video rate so that the array can be read like a camera.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Using this technique many thousands of pixels / channels may be acquired simultaneously.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] High resolution 3-D lidar cameras use homodyne detection with an electronic CCD or CMOS shutter.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] A coherent imaging lidar uses synthetic array heterodyne detection to enable a staring single element receiver to act as though it were an imaging array.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] In 2014, Lincoln Laboratory announced a new imaging chip with more than 16,384 pixels, each able to image a single photon, enabling them to capture a wide area in a single image.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] An earlier generation of the technology with one fourth as many pixels was dispatched by the U.S. military after the January 2010 Haiti earthquake.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] A single pass by a business jet at 3,000 m (10,000 ft) over Port-au-Prince was able to capture instantaneous snapshots of 600 m (2,000 ft) squares of the city at a resolution of 30 cm (1 ft), displaying the precise height of rubble strewn in city streets.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The new system is ten times better, and could produce much larger maps more quickly.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The chip uses indium gallium arsenide (InGaAs), which operates in the infrared spectrum at a relatively long wavelength that allows for higher power and longer ranges.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] In many applications, such as self-driving cars, the new system will lower costs by not requiring a mechanical component to aim the chip.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] InGaAs uses less hazardous wavelengths than conventional silicon detectors, which operate at visual wavelengths.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] New technologies for infrared single-photon counting lidar are advancing rapidly, including arrays and cameras in a variety of semiconductor and superconducting platforms.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Lidar can be oriented to nadir, zenith, or laterally.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] For example, lidar altimeters look down, an atmospheric lidar looks up, and lidar-based collision avoidance systems are side-looking.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Lidar applications can be divided into airborne and terrestrial types.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The two types require scanners with varying specifications based on the data's purpose, the size of the area to be captured, the range of measurement desired, the cost of equipment, and more.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Spaceborne platforms are also possible, see satellite laser altimetry.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar (also *airborne laser scanning*) is when a laser scanner, while attached to an aircraft during flight, creates a 3-D point cloud model of the landscape.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] This is currently the most detailed and accurate method of creating digital elevation models, replacing photogrammetry.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] One major advantage in comparison with photogrammetry is the ability to filter out reflections from vegetation from the point cloud model to create a digital terrain model which represents ground surfaces such as rivers, paths, cultural heritage sites, etc., which are concealed by trees.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Within the category of airborne lidar, there is sometimes a distinction made between high-altitude and low-altitude applications, but the main difference is a reduction in both accuracy and point density of data acquired at higher altitudes.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar can also be used to create bathymetric models in shallow water.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The main constituents of airborne lidar include digital elevation models (DEM) and digital surface models (DSM).
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The points and ground points are the vectors of discrete points while DEM and DSM are interpolated raster grids of discrete points.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The process also involves capturing of digital aerial photographs.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] To interpret deep-seated landslides for example, under the cover of vegetation, scarps, tension cracks or tipped trees airborne lidar is used.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar digital elevation models can see through the canopy of forest cover, perform detailed measurements of scarps, erosion and tilting of electric poles.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar data is processed using a toolbox called Toolbox for Lidar Data Filtering and Forest Studies (TIFFS) for lidar data filtering and terrain study software.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The data is interpolated to digital terrain models using the software.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The laser is directed at the region to be mapped and each point's height above the ground is calculated by subtracting the original z-coordinate from the corresponding digital terrain model elevation.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Based on this height above the ground the non-vegetation data is obtained which may include objects such as buildings, electric power lines, flying birds, insects, etc.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The rest of the points are treated as vegetation and used for modeling and mapping.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Within each of these plots, lidar metrics are calculated by calculating statistics such as mean, standard deviation, skewness, percentiles, quadratic mean, etc.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Multiple commercial lidar systems for unmanned aerial vehicles are currently on the market.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] These platforms can systematically scan large areas, or provide a cheaper alternative to manned aircraft for smaller scanning operations.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The airborne lidar bathymetric technological system involves the measurement of time of flight of a signal from a source to its return to the sensor.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The data acquisition technique involves a sea floor mapping component and a ground truth component that includes video transects and sampling.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] It works using a green spectrum (532 nm) laser beam.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Two beams are projected onto a fast rotating mirror, which creates an array of points.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] One of the beams penetrates the water and also detects the bottom surface of the water under favorable conditions.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Water depth measurable by lidar depends on the clarity of the water and the absorption of the wavelength used.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Water is most transparent to green and blue light, so these will penetrate deepest in clean water.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Blue-green light of 532 nm produced by frequency doubled solid-state IR laser output is the standard for airborne bathymetry.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] This light can penetrate water but pulse strength attenuates exponentially with distance traveled through the water.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Lidar can measure depths from about 0.9 to 40 m (3 to 131 ft), with vertical accuracy in the order of 15 cm (6 in).
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The surface reflection makes water shallower than about 0.9 m (3 ft) difficult to resolve, and absorption limits the maximum depth.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Turbidity causes scattering and has a significant role in determining the maximum depth that can be resolved in most situations, and dissolved pigments can increase absorption depending on wavelength.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Other reports indicate that water penetration tends to be between two and three times Secchi depth.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Bathymetric lidar is most useful in the 0–10 m (0–33 ft) depth range in coastal mapping.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] On average in fairly clear coastal seawater lidar can penetrate to about 7 m (23 ft), and in turbid water up to about 3 m (10 ft).
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] An average value found by Saputra et al, 2021, is for the green laser light to penetrate water about one and a half to two times Secchi depth in Indonesian waters.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Water temperature and salinity have an effect on the refractive index which has a small effect on the depth calculation.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The data obtained shows the full extent of the land surface exposed above the sea floor.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] This technique is extremely useful as it will play an important role in the major sea floor mapping program.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The mapping yields onshore topography as well as underwater elevations.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Sea floor reflectance imaging is another solution product from this system which can benefit mapping of underwater habitats.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] This technique has been used for three-dimensional image mapping of California's waters using a hydrographic lidar.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar systems were traditionally able to acquire only a few peak returns, while more recent systems acquire and digitize the entire reflected signal.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Scientists analysed the waveform signal for extracting peak returns using Gaussian decomposition.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Zhuang et al, 2017 used this approach for estimating aboveground biomass.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Handling the huge amounts of full-waveform data is difficult.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Therefore, Gaussian decomposition of the waveforms is effective, since it reduces the data and is supported by existing workflows that support interpretation of 3-D point clouds.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Recent studies investigated voxelisation.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The intensities of the waveform samples are inserted into a voxelised space (3-D grayscale image) building up a 3-D representation of the scanned area.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Related metrics and information can then be extracted from that voxelised space.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Structural information can be extracted using 3-D metrics from local areas and there is a case study that used the voxelisation approach for detecting dead standing eucalypt trees in Australia.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Terrestrial applications of lidar (also *terrestrial laser scanning*) happen on the Earth's surface and can be either stationary or mobile.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Stationary terrestrial scanning is most common as a survey method, for example in conventional topography, monitoring, cultural heritage documentation and forensics.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The 3-D point clouds acquired from these types of scanners can be matched with digital images taken of the scanned area from the scanner's location to create realistic looking 3-D models in a relatively short time when compared to other technologies.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Each point in the point cloud is given the colour of the pixel from the image taken at the same location and direction as the laser beam that created the point.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Terrestrial lidar mapping involves a process of occupancy grid map generation.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The process involves an array of cells divided into grids which employ a process to store the height values when lidar data falls into the respective grid cell.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] A binary map is then created by applying a particular threshold to the cell values for further processing.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] The next step is to process the radial distance and z-coordinates from each scan to identify which 3-D points correspond to each of the specified grid cell leading to the process of data formation.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Mobile lidar (also *mobile laser scanning*) is when two or more scanners are attached to a moving vehicle to collect data along a path.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] These scanners are almost always paired with other kinds of equipment, including GNSS receivers and IMUs.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] One example application is surveying streets, where power lines, exact bridge heights, bordering trees, etc. all need to be taken into account.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] Instead of collecting each of these measurements individually in the field with a tachymeter, a 3-D model from a point cloud can be created where all of the measurements needed can be made, depending on the quality of the data collected.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p01] This eliminates the problem of forgetting to take a measurement, so long as the model is available, reliable and has an appropriate level of accuracy.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] There are a wide variety of lidar applications, in addition to the applications listed below, as it is often mentioned in national lidar dataset programs.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Companies are working to cut the cost of lidar sensors, currently anywhere from about US$1,200 to more than $12,000.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lower prices will make lidar more attractive for new markets.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Agricultural robots have been used for a variety of purposes ranging from seed and fertilizer dispersions, sensing techniques as well as crop scouting for the task of weed control.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar can help determine where to apply costly fertilizer.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] It can create a topographical map of the fields and reveal slopes and sun exposure of the farmland.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Researchers at the Agricultural Research Service used this topographical data with the farmland yield results from previous years, to categorize land into zones of high, medium, or low yield.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] This indicates where to apply fertilizer to maximize yield.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar is now used to monitor insects in the field.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The use of lidar can detect the movement and behavior of individual flying insects, with identification down to sex and species.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In 2017 a patent application was published on this technology in the United States, Europe, and China.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Another application is crop mapping in orchards and vineyards, to detect foliage growth and the need for pruning or other maintenance, detect variations in fruit production, or count plants.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar is useful in GNSS-denied situations, such as nut and fruit orchards, where foliage causes interference for agriculture equipment that would otherwise utilize a precise GNSS fix.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar sensors can detect and track the relative position of rows, plants, and other markers so that farming equipment can continue operating until a GNSS fix is reestablished.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Controlling weeds requires identifying plant species.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] This can be done by using 3-D lidar and machine learning.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar produces plant contours as a "point cloud" with range and reflectance values.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] This data is transformed, and features are extracted from it.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] If the species is known, the features are added as new data.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The species is labelled and its features are initially stored as an example to identify the species in the real environment.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] This method is efficient because it uses a low-resolution lidar and supervised learning.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] It includes an easy-to-compute feature set with common statistical features which are independent of the plant size.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In April 2025, Dallas Fort Worth International Airport announced the deployment of a lidar-based platform for real-time monitoring of passenger and vehicle flows.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar has many uses in archaeology, including planning of field campaigns, mapping features under forest canopy, and overview of broad, continuous features indistinguishable from the ground.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar can produce high-resolution datasets quickly and cheaply.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar-derived products can be easily integrated into a geographic information system (GIS) for analysis and interpretation.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar can also help to create high-resolution digital elevation models (DEMs) of archaeological sites that can reveal micro-topography that is otherwise hidden by vegetation.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The intensity of the returned lidar signal can be used to detect features buried under flat vegetated surfaces such as fields, especially when mapping using the infrared spectrum.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The presence of these features affects plant growth and thus the amount of infrared light reflected back.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] For example, at Fort Beauséjour – Fort Cumberland National Historic Site, Canada, lidar discovered archaeological features related to the siege of the Fort in 1755.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Features that could not be distinguished on the ground or through aerial photography were identified by overlaying hill shades of the DEM created with artificial illumination from various angles.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Another example is work at Caracol by Arlen Chase and his wife Diane Zaino Chase.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In 2012, lidar was used to search for the legendary city of La Ciudad Blanca or "City of the Monkey God" in the La Mosquitia region of the Honduran jungle.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] During a seven-day mapping period, evidence was found of man-made structures.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In June 2013, the rediscovery of the city of Mahendraparvata was announced.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In southern New England, lidar was used to reveal stone walls, building foundations, abandoned roads, and other landscape features obscured in aerial photography by the region's dense forest canopy.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In Cambodia, lidar data were used by Damian Evans and Roland Fletcher to reveal anthropogenic changes to Angkor landscape.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In 2012, lidar revealed that the Purépecha settlement of Angamuco in Michoacán, Mexico had about as many buildings as today's Manhattan; while in 2016, its use in mapping ancient Maya causeways in northern Guatemala, revealed 17 elevated roads linking the ancient city of El Mirador to other sites.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In 2018, archaeologists using lidar discovered more than 60,000 man-made structures in the Maya Biosphere Reserve, a "major breakthrough" that showed the Maya civilization was much larger than previously thought.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In 2024, archaeologists using lidar discovered the Upano Valley sites.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Autonomous vehicles may use lidar for obstacle detection and avoidance to navigate safely through environments.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The introduction of lidar was a pivotal occurrence that was the key enabler behind Stanley, the first autonomous vehicle to successfully complete the DARPA Grand Challenge.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Point cloud output from the lidar sensor provides the necessary data for robot software to determine where potential obstacles exist in the environment and where the robot is in relation to those potential obstacles.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Singapore's *Singapore-MIT Alliance for Research and Technology (SMART)* is actively developing technologies for autonomous lidar vehicles.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The very first generations of automotive adaptive cruise control systems used only lidar sensors.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In transportation systems, to ensure vehicle and passenger safety and to develop electronic systems that deliver driver assistance, understanding the vehicle and its surrounding environment is essential.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar systems play an important role in the safety of transportation systems.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Many electronic systems which enhance driver assistance and vehicle safety such as adaptive cruise control (ACC), emergency brake assist, and anti-lock braking system (ABS) depend on the detection of a vehicle's environment to act autonomously or semi-autonomously.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar mapping and estimation achieve this.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Current lidar systems use rotating hexagonal mirrors which split the laser beam.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The upper three beams are used for vehicle and obstacles ahead, and the lower beams are used to detect lane markings and road features.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The major advantage of using lidar is that the spatial structure is obtained and this data can be fused with other sensors such as radar, etc. to get a better picture of the vehicle environment in terms of static and dynamic properties of the objects present in the environment.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Conversely, a significant issue with lidar is the difficulty in reconstructing point cloud data in poor weather conditions.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In heavy rain, for example, the light pulses emitted from the lidar system are partially reflected off of rain droplets which adds noise to the data, called 'echoes'.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Obstacle detection and road environment recognition using lidar, proposed by Kun Zhou et al. not only focuses on object detection and tracking but also recognizes lane marking and road features.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] As mentioned earlier, the lidar systems use rotating hexagonal mirrors that split the laser beam into six beams.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The upper three layers are used to detect the forward objects such as vehicles and roadside objects.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The sensor is made of weather-resistant material.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The data detected by lidar are clustered to several segments and tracked by Kalman filter.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Data clustering here is done based on characteristics of each segment based on object model, which distinguish different objects such as vehicles, signboards, etc.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] These characteristics include the dimensions of the object, etc.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The reflectors on the rear edges of vehicles are used to differentiate vehicles from other objects.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Object tracking is done using a two-stage Kalman filter considering the stability of tracking and the accelerated motion of objects Lidar reflective intensity data is also used for curb detection by making use of robust regression to deal with occlusions.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Road marking is detected using a modified Otsu method by distinguishing rough and shiny surfaces.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Roadside reflectors that indicate lane border are sometimes hidden due to various reasons.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Therefore, other information is needed to recognize the road border.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The lidar used in this method can measure the reflectivity from the object.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Hence, with this data the road border can also be recognized.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Also, the usage of a sensor with a weather-robust head helps to detect the objects even in bad weather conditions.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Canopy height model before and after a flood is a good example.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar can detect highly detailed canopy height data as well as its road border.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar measurements help identify the spatial structure of the obstacle.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] This helps distinguish objects based on size and estimate the impact of driving over it.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar systems provide better range and a large field of view, which helps in detecting obstacles on the curves.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] This is one of its major advantages over radar systems, which have a narrower field of view.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The fusion of lidar measurement with different sensors makes the system robust and useful in real-time applications, since lidar-dependent systems cannot estimate the dynamic information about the detected object.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] It has been shown that lidar can be manipulated, such that self-driving cars are tricked into taking evasive action.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar has also found many applications for mapping natural and managed landscapes such as forests, wetlands, and grasslands.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Canopy heights, biomass measurements, and leaf area can all be studied using airborne lidar systems.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Similarly, lidar is also used by many industries, including Energy and Railroad, and the Department of Transportation as a faster way of surveying.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Topographic maps can also be generated readily from lidar, including for recreational use such as in the production of orienteering maps.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar has also been applied to estimate and assess the biodiversity of plants, fungi, and animals.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Using southern bull kelp in New Zealand, coastal lidar mapping data has been compared with population genomic evidence to form hypotheses regarding the occurrence and timing of prehistoric earthquake uplift events.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar systems have also been applied to improve forestry management.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Measurements are used to take inventory in forest plots as well as calculate individual tree heights, crown width and crown diameter.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Other statistical analysis use lidar data to estimate total plot information such as canopy volume, mean, minimum and maximum heights, vegetation cover, biomass, and carbon density.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Aerial lidar was used to map the bush fires in Australia in early 2020.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The data was manipulated to view bare earth, and identify healthy and burned vegetation.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] High-resolution digital elevation maps generated by airborne and stationary lidar have led to significant advances in geomorphology (the branch of geoscience concerned with the origin and evolution of the Earth surface topography).
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In 2005 the Tour Ronde in the Mont Blanc massif became the first high alpine mountain on which lidar was employed to monitor the increasing occurrence of severe rock-fall over large rock faces allegedly caused by climate change and degradation of permafrost at high altitude.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar is also used in structural geology and geophysics as a combination between airborne lidar and GNSS for the detection and study of faults, for measuring uplift.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The output of the two technologies can produce extremely accurate elevation models for terrain – models that can even measure ground elevation through trees.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] This combination was used most famously to find the location of the Seattle Fault in Washington, United States.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] This combination also measures uplift at Mount St.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Helens by using data from before and after the 2004 uplift.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Airborne lidar systems monitor glaciers and have the ability to detect subtle amounts of growth or decline.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] A satellite-based system, the NASA ICESat, includes a lidar sub-system for this purpose.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The NASA Airborne Topographic Mapper is also used extensively to monitor glaciers and perform coastal change analysis.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The combination is also used by soil scientists while creating a soil survey.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The detailed terrain modeling allows soil scientists to see slope changes and landform breaks which indicate patterns in soil spatial relationships.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Initially, based on ruby lasers, lidar for meteorological applications was constructed shortly after the invention of the laser and represents one of the first applications of laser technology.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar technology has since expanded vastly in capability and lidar systems are used to perform a range of measurements that include profiling clouds, measuring winds, studying aerosols, and quantifying various atmospheric components.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Atmospheric components can in turn provide useful information including surface pressure (by measuring the absorption of oxygen or nitrogen), greenhouse gas emissions (carbon dioxide and methane), photosynthesis (carbon dioxide), fires (carbon monoxide), and humidity (water vapor).
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Atmospheric lidars can be either ground-based, airborne or satellite-based depending on the type of measurement.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] 2. by measuring the scattered reflection off the ground (when the lidar is airborne) or other hard surface.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Backscatter from the atmosphere directly gives a measure of clouds and aerosols.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Other derived measurements from backscatter such as winds or cirrus ice crystals require careful selecting of the wavelength and/or polarization detected.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] *Doppler lidar* and *Rayleigh Doppler lidar* are used to measure temperature and wind speed along the beam by measuring the frequency of the backscattered light.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The Doppler broadening of gases in motion allows the determination of properties via the resulting frequency shift.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Scanning lidars, such as NASA's conical-scanning HARLIE, have been used to measure atmospheric wind velocity.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The ESA wind mission *ADM-Aeolus* will be equipped with a Doppler lidar system in order to provide global measurements of vertical wind profiles.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] A doppler lidar system was used in the 2008 Summer Olympics to measure wind fields during the yacht competition.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Doppler lidar systems are also now beginning to be successfully applied in the renewable energy sector to acquire wind speed, turbulence, wind veer, and wind shear data.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Both pulsed and continuous wave systems are being used.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Pulsed systems use signal timing to obtain vertical distance resolution, whereas continuous wave systems rely on detector focusing.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The term *eolics* has been proposed to describe the collaborative and interdisciplinary study of wind using computational fluid mechanics simulations and Doppler lidar measurements.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The ground reflection of an airborne lidar gives a measure of surface reflectivity (assuming the atmospheric transmittance is well known) at the lidar wavelength, however, the ground reflection is typically used for making absorption measurements of the atmosphere.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] "Differential absorption lidar" (DIAL) measurements utilize two or more closely spaced (less than 1 nm) wavelengths to factor out surface reflectivity as well as other transmission losses, since these factors are relatively insensitive to wavelength.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] When tuned to the appropriate absorption lines of a particular gas, DIAL measurements can be used to determine the concentration (mixing ratio) of that particular gas in the atmosphere.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] This is referred to as an *integrated path differential absorption* (IPDA) approach, since it is a measure of the integrated absorption along the entire lidar path.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] IPDA lidars can be either pulsed or CW and typically use two or more wavelengths.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] IPDA lidars have been used for remote sensing of carbon dioxide and methane.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In Japan, differential absorption lidar (DIAL) and Raman lidar technologies are being developed to improve the accuracy of flood forecasting and rainfall prediction.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] A research by several companies, universities, and institutes, led by Kyushu University is conducting work on meteorological sensing and flood-risk modelling under a government program.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In May 2025, EKO Instruments began a field study on Goto Fukue Island, Nagasaki Prefecture, using a Micropulse DIAL lidar system provided by the National Center for Atmospheric Research (NSF NCAR).
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The study compares DIAL performance with existing Raman lidar systems.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Ltd. signed a technology license agreement in February 2025 with Montana State University, NSF NCAR, and NASA, covering key DIAL-related patents.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Few military applications are known to be in place and are classified (such as the lidar-based speed measurement of the AGM-129 ACM stealth nuclear cruise missile), but a considerable amount of research is underway in their use for imaging.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Higher resolution systems collect enough detail to identify targets, such as tanks.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Examples of military applications of lidar include the Airborne Laser Mine Detection System (ALMDS) for counter-mine warfare by Areté Associates.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] A NATO report (RTO-TR-SET-098) evaluated the potential technologies to do stand-off detection for the discrimination of biological warfare agents.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The potential technologies evaluated were long-wave infrared (LWIR), differential scattering (DISC), and ultraviolet laser-induced fluorescence (UV-LIF).
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Short-range compact spectrometric lidar based on laser-induced fluorescence (LIF) would address the presence of bio-threats in aerosol form over critical indoor, semi-enclosed and outdoor venues such as stadiums, subways, and airports.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] This near real-time capability would enable rapid detection of a bioaerosol release and allow for timely implementation of measures to protect occupants and minimize the extent of contamination.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The Long-Range Biological Standoff Detection System (LR-BSDS) was developed for the U.S.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Army to provide the earliest possible standoff warning of a biological attack.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] It is an airborne system carried by helicopter to detect synthetic aerosol clouds containing biological and chemical agents at long range.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The LR-BSDS, with a detection range of 30 km or more, was fielded in June 1997.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Five lidar units produced by the German company Sick AG were used for short range detection on Stanley, the autonomous car that won the 2005 DARPA Grand Challenge.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] A robotic Boeing AH-6 performed a fully autonomous flight in June 2010, including avoiding obstacles using lidar.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The calculation of ore volumes is accomplished by periodic (monthly) scanning in areas of ore removal, then comparing surface data to the previous scan.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar sensors may also be used for obstacle detection and avoidance for robotic mining vehicles such as in the Komatsu Autonomous Haulage System (AHS) used in Rio Tinto's Mine of the Future.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] A worldwide network of observatories uses lidars to measure the distance to reflectors placed on the Moon, allowing the position of the Moon to be measured with millimeter precision and tests of general relativity to be done.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] MOLA, the Mars Orbiting Laser Altimeter, used a lidar instrument in a Mars-orbiting satellite (the NASA Mars Global Surveyor) to produce a spectacularly precise global topographic survey of the red planet.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Laser altimeters produced global elevation models of Mars, the Moon (Lunar Orbiter Laser Altimeter (LOLA)), and Mercury (Mercury Laser Altimeter (MLA), NEAR–Shoemaker Laser Rangefinder (NLR)).
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Future missions will also include laser altimeter experiments such as the Ganymede Laser Altimeter (GALA) as part of the Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer (JUICE) mission.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In September, 2008, the NASA *Phoenix* lander used lidar to detect snow in the atmosphere of Mars.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In atmospheric physics, lidar is used as a remote detection instrument to measure densities of certain constituents of the middle and upper atmosphere, such as potassium, sodium, or molecular nitrogen and oxygen.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] These measurements can be used to calculate temperatures.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar can also be used to measure wind speed and to provide information about vertical distribution of the aerosol particles.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] At the JET nuclear fusion research facility in the UK near Abingdon, Oxfordshire, lidar Thomson scattering is used to determine electron density and temperature profiles of the plasma.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar has been widely used in rock mechanics for rock mass characterization and slope change detection.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Some important geomechanical properties from the rock mass can be extracted from the 3-D point clouds obtained by means of the lidar.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Some of these properties have been used to assess the geomechanical quality of the rock mass through the RMR index.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Moreover, as the orientations of discontinuities can be extracted using the existing methodologies, it is possible to assess the geomechanical quality of a rock slope through the SMR index.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In addition to this, the comparison of different 3-D point clouds from a slope acquired at different times allows researchers to study the changes produced on the scene during this time interval as a result of rockfalls or any other landsliding processes.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] THOR is a laser designed toward measuring Earth's atmospheric conditions.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The laser enters a cloud cover and measures the thickness of the return halo.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The sensor has a fiber optic aperture with a width of 7+1⁄2 inches (19 cm) that is used to measure the return light.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar technology is being used in robotics for the perception of the environment as well as object classification.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The ability of lidar technology to provide three-dimensional elevation maps of the terrain, high precision distance to the ground, and approach velocity can enable safe landing of robotic and crewed vehicles with a high degree of precision.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar is also widely used in robotics for simultaneous localization and mapping and is well-integrated into robot simulators.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Refer to the Military section above for further examples.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar is increasingly being utilized for rangefinding and orbital element calculation of relative velocity in proximity operations and stationkeeping of spacecraft.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar has also been used for atmospheric studies from space.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Short pulses of laser light beamed from a spacecraft can reflect off tiny particles in the atmosphere and back to a telescope aligned with the spacecraft laser.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] By precisely timing the lidar echo, and by measuring how much laser light is received by the telescope, scientists can accurately determine the location, distribution and nature of the particles.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The result is a revolutionary new tool for studying constituents in the atmosphere, from cloud droplets to industrial pollutants, which are difficult to detect by other means.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Laser altimetry is used to make digital elevation maps of planets, including the Mars Orbital Laser Altimeter (MOLA) mapping of Mars, the Lunar Orbital Laser Altimeter (LOLA) and Lunar Altimeter (LALT) mapping of the Moon, and the Mercury Laser Altimeter (MLA) mapping of Mercury.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] It is also used to help navigate the helicopter *Ingenuity* in its record-setting flights over the terrain of Mars.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Airborne lidar sensors are used by companies in the remote sensing field.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] They can be used to create a DTM (digital terrain model) or DEM (digital elevation model); this is quite a common practice for larger areas as a plane can acquire 3–4 km (2–2+1⁄2 mi) wide swaths in a single flyover.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Greater vertical accuracy of below 50 mm (2 in) can be achieved with a lower flyover, even in forests, where it is able to give the height of the canopy as well as the ground elevation.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Typically, a GNSS receiver configured over a georeferenced control point is needed to link the data in with the WGS (World Geodetic System).
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar is also in use in hydrographic surveying.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Depending upon the clarity of the water lidar can measure depths from 0.9 to 40 m (3 to 131 ft) with a vertical accuracy of 15 cm (6 in) and horizontal accuracy of 2.5 m (8 ft).
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar has been used in the railroad industry to generate asset health reports for asset management and by departments of transportation to assess their road conditions.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] CivilMaps.com is a leading company in the field.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar has been used in adaptive cruise control (ACC) systems for automobiles.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Systems such as those by Siemens, Hella, Ouster and Cepton use a lidar device mounted on the front of the vehicle, such as the bumper, to monitor the distance between the vehicle and any vehicle in front of it.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In the event where the vehicle in front slows down or is too close, the ACC applies the brakes to slow the vehicle.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] When the road ahead is clear, the ACC allows the vehicle to accelerate to a speed preset by the driver.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] A lidar-based device, the Ceilometer, is used at airports worldwide to measure the height of clouds on runway approach paths.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar can be used to increase the energy output from wind farms by accurately measuring wind speeds and wind turbulence.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Experimental lidar systems can be mounted on the nacelle of a wind turbine or integrated into the rotating spinner to measure oncoming horizontal winds, winds in the wake of the wind turbine, and proactively adjust blades to protect components and increase power.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar is also used to characterise the incident wind resource for comparison with wind turbine power production to verify the performance of the wind turbine by measuring the wind turbine's power curve.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Wind farm optimization can be considered a topic in *applied eolics*.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Another aspect of lidar in wind related industry is to use computational fluid dynamics over lidar-scanned surfaces in order to assess the wind potential, which can be used for optimal wind farm placement.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar can also be used to assist planners and developers in optimizing solar photovoltaic systems at the city level by determining appropriate roof tops and for determining shading losses.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Recent airborne laser scanning efforts have focused on ways to estimate the amount of solar light hitting vertical building facades, or by incorporating more detailed shading losses by considering the influence from vegetation and larger surrounding terrain.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The 2017 exploration game *Scanner Sombre*, by Introversion Software, uses lidar as a fundamental game mechanic.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In *Build the Earth*, lidar is used to create accurate renders of terrain in *Minecraft* to account for any errors (mainly regarding elevation) in the default generation.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The process of rendering terrain into Build the Earth is limited by the amount of data available in region as well as the speed it takes to convert the file into block data.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Lidar technology enhances physical security by providing precise, privacy-compliant threat detection for applications such as perimeter protection, building facades, and critical infrastructure monitoring.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] These systems utilize laser-based sensors to create high-density point clouds that function reliably in challenging environmental conditions, including rain, snow, and complete darkness.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] A key advantage of modern systems is the use of 3D lidar, which creates precise volumetric detection zones capturing height, width, and depth, allowing for the accurate classification of object size and movement speed.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The video for the 2007 song "House of Cards" by Radiohead was believed to be the first use of real-time 3-D laser scanning to record a music video.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The range data in the video is not completely from a lidar, as structured light scanning is also used.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In 2020, Apple introduced the fourth generation of iPad Pro with a lidar sensor integrated into the rear camera module, especially developed for augmented reality (AR) experiences.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The feature was later included in the iPhone 12 Pro lineup and subsequent Pro models.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] On Apple devices, lidar empowers portrait mode pictures with night mode, quickens auto focus and improves accuracy in the Measure app.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In 2022, *Wheel of Fortune* started using lidar technology to track when Vanna White moves her hand over the puzzle board to reveal letters.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The first episode to have this technology was in the season 40 premiere.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In flash lidar, the entire field of view is illuminated with a wide diverging laser beam in a single pulse.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] This is in contrast to conventional scanning lidar, which uses a collimated laser beam that illuminates a single point at a time, and the beam is raster scanned to illuminate the field of view point-by-point.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] This illumination method requires a different detection scheme as well.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In both scanning and flash lidar, a time-of-flight camera is used to collect information about both the 3-D location and intensity of the light incident on it in every frame.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] However, in scanning lidar, this camera contains only a point sensor, while in flash lidar, the camera contains either a 1-D or a 2-D sensor array, each pixel of which collects 3-D location and intensity information.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] In both cases, the depth information is collected using the time of flight of the laser pulse (i.e., the time it takes each laser pulse to hit the target and return to the sensor), which requires the pulsing of the laser and acquisition by the camera to be synchronized.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The result is a camera that takes pictures of distance, instead of colors.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Flash lidar is especially advantageous when compared to scanning lidar, when the camera, scene, or both are moving, since the entire scene is illuminated at the same time.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] With scanning lidar, motion can cause "jitter" from the lapse in time as the laser rasters over the scene.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] As with all forms of lidar, the onboard source of illumination makes flash lidar an active sensor.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The signal that is returned is processed by embedded algorithms to produce a nearly instantaneous 3-D rendering of objects and terrain features within the field of view of the sensor.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The laser pulse repetition frequency is sufficient for generating 3-D videos with high resolution and accuracy.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The high frame rate of the sensor makes it a useful tool for a variety of applications that benefit from real-time visualization, such as highly precise remote landing operations.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] By immediately returning a 3-D elevation mesh of target landscapes, a flash sensor can be used to identify optimal landing zones in autonomous spacecraft landing scenarios.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Seeing at a distance requires a powerful burst of light.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] The power is limited to levels that do not damage human retinas.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] However, low-cost silicon imagers do not read light in the eye-safe spectrum.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Instead, gallium-arsenide imagers are required, which can boost costs to $200,000.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Gallium-arsenide is the same compound used to produce high-cost, high-efficiency solar panels usually used in space applications.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] Computer stereo vision has shown promise as an alternative to lidar for close-range applications.
[src:self-driving-perception/lidar-p02] It is significantly more cost effective when appropriate.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] It is widely used in computer vision tasks such as image annotation, vehicle counting, activity recognition, face detection, face recognition, video object co-segmentation.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] It is also used in tracking objects, for example tracking a ball during a football match, tracking movement of a cricket bat, or tracking a person in a video.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] Often, the test images are sampled from a different data distribution, making the object detection task significantly more difficult.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] To address the challenges caused by the domain gap between training and test data, many unsupervised domain adaptation approaches have been proposed.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] A simple and straightforward solution for reducing the domain gap is to apply an image-to-image translation approach, such as cycle-GAN.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] Among other uses, cross-domain object detection is applied in autonomous driving, where models can be trained on a vast amount of video game scenes, since the labels can be generated without manual labor.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] Every object class has its own special features that help in classifying the class – for example all circles are round.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] Object class detection uses these special features.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] For example, when looking for circles, objects that are at a particular distance from a point (i.e. the center) are sought.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] Similarly, when looking for squares, objects that are perpendicular at corners and have equal side lengths are needed.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] A similar approach is used for face identification where eyes, nose, and lips can be found and features like skin color and distance between eyes can be found.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] For object localization, true positive is often measured by the thresholded intersection over union.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] For example, if there is a traffic sign in the image, with a bounding box drawn by a human ("ground truth label"), then a neural network has detected the traffic sign (a **true positive**) at 0.5 threshold if it has drawn a bounding box whose IoU with the ground truth is above 0.5.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] Otherwise, the bounding box is a **false positive**.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] If there is only a single ground truth bounding box, but multiple predictions, then the IoU of each prediction is calculated.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] The prediction with the highest IoU is a true positive if it is above threshold, else it is a false positive.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] All other predicted bounding boxes are false positives.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] If there is no prediction with an IoU above the threshold, then the ground truth label has a **false negative**.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] For simultaneous object localization and classification, a true positive is one where the class label is correct, and the bounding box has an IoU exceeding the threshold.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] Simultaneous object localization and classification is benchmarked by the **mean average precision** (mAP).
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] The average precision (AP) of the network for a class of objects is the area under the precision-recall curve as the confidence threshold is varied.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] The mAP is the average of AP over all classes.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] However, the instance of a ring textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] Methods for object detection generally fall into either neural network-based or non-neural approaches.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] For non-neural approaches, it becomes necessary to first define features using one of the methods below, then using a technique such as support vector machine (SVM) to do the classification.
[src:self-driving-perception/object-detection] On the other hand, neural techniques are able to do end-to-end object detection without specifically defining features, and are typically based on convolutional neural networks (CNN).
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] The concept of optic flow has roots as far back as Euclid's *Optics*, but its modern formulation arose from Second World War research into pilot vision during landing.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Several researchers arrived at the idea independently; James J.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Gibson gave it its most influential treatment, publishing his theory in 1947 and created the term "optic flow" in 1950.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Optical flow can be estimated in a number of ways.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Many classical models use the intuitive assumption of *brightness constancy*; that even if a point moves between frames, its brightness stays constant.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] To formalise this intuitive assumption, consider two consecutive frames from a video sequence, with intensity $I(x,y,t)$ , where $(x,y)$ refer to pixel coordinates and t refers to time.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] where $\mathbf {w$ is the displacement vector between a point in the first frame and the corresponding point in the second frame.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] By itself, the brightness constancy constraint cannot be solved for u and v at each pixel, since there is only one equation and two unknowns.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] This is known as the *aperture problem*.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Therefore, additional constraints must be imposed to estimate the flow field.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Perhaps the most natural approach to addressing the aperture problem is to apply a smoothness constraint or a *regularization constraint* to the flow field.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] where $\Omega$ is the extent of the images $I(x,y)$ , $\nabla$ is the gradient operator, $\alpha$ is a constant, and $\Psi ()$ is a loss function.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] This optimisation problem is difficult to solve owing to its non-linearity.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] To address this issue, one can use a *variational approach* and linearise the brightness constancy constraint using a first order Taylor series approximation.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] For convenience, the derivatives of the image, ${\tfrac {\partial I}{\partial x}}$ , ${\tfrac {\partial I}{\partial y}}$ and ${\tfrac {\partial I}{\partial t}}$ are often condensed to become $I_{x}$ , $I_{y}$ and $I_{t}$ .
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] For the choice of $\Psi (x)=x^{2}$ , this method is the same as the Horn-Schunck method.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Of course, other choices of cost function have been used such as $\Psi (x)={\sqrt {x^{2}+\epsilon ^{2}}}$ , which is a differentiable variant of the $L^{1}$ norm.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] To solve the aforementioned optimization problem, one can use the Euler-Lagrange equations to provide a system of partial differential equations for each point in $I(x,y,t)$ .
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Since the image data is made up of discrete pixels, these equations are discretised.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Doing so yields a system of linear equations which can be solved for $(u,v)$ at each pixel, using an iterative scheme such as Gauss-Seidel.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Although, linearising the brightness constancy constraint simplifies the optimisation problem significantly, the linearisation is only valid for small displacements and/or smooth images.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] To avoid this problem, a multi-scale or coarse-to-fine approach is often used.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] In such a scheme, the images are initially downsampled and the linearised Euler-Lagrange equations are solved at the reduced resolution.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] The estimated flow field at this scale is then used to initialise the process at next scale.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] This initialisation process is often performed by warping one frame using the current estimate of flow field so that it is as similar to other as possible.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] An alternate approach is to discretize the optimisation problem and then perform a search of the possible $(u,v)$ values without linearising it.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] This search is often performed using Max-flow min-cut theorem algorithms, linear programming or belief propagation methods.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] These regularized methods typically require manual tuning of the Lagrange multiplier, the so-called regularization parameters.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] There has been some progress in the automatic determination of these parameters in the context of optical flow applied to particle image velocimetry (PIV) data.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Instead of applying the regularization constraint on a point by point basis as per a regularized model, one can group pixels into regions and estimate the motion of these regions.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] This is known as a *parametric model*, since the motion of these regions is parameterized.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] In formulating optical flow estimation in this way, one makes the assumption that the motion field in each region be fully characterised by a set of parameters.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] The simplest parametric model is the Lucas-Kanade method.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] This uses rectangular regions and parameterises the motion as purely translational.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] The Lucas-Kanade method uses the original brightness constancy constraint as the data cost term and selects $g(x,y)=1$ .
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Other possible local loss functions include the negative normalized cross-correlation between the two frames.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Instead of seeking to model optical flow directly, one can train a machine learning system to estimate optical flow.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Since 2015, when FlowNet was proposed, learning based models have been applied to optical flow and have gained prominence.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] However, with the advent of transformer architecture in 2017, transformer based models have gained prominence.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] A significant shift occurred with the introduction of RAFT (Recurrent All-Pairs Field Transforms), which replaced coarse-to-fine pyramids with a single GRU-based state that iteratively updates the flow field.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] By maintaining a constant feature resolution at 1/8 of the input, RAFT significantly improved the preservation of fine details and robustness to fast motion compared to previous bottleneck-heavy designs, influencing a wide range of subsequent models that adopt similar iterative update mechanisms.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] However, the all-pairs correlation used in such models is computationally expensive; for high-resolution content like FullHD or 4K, global matching can require more than 32 GB of VRAM, making it impractical for consumer-grade GPUs.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] To address this, efficiency-focused methods such as Flow1D, MeFlow, and Memfof have been developed.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] While these approaches generally optimize memory usage by decomposing the 2D search space, the latter optimizes correlation volumes for high-resolution multi-frame sequences, providing a practical implementation for standard GPUs.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Most learning-based approaches to optical flow use supervised learning.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] In this case, many frame pairs of video data and their corresponding ground-truth flow fields are used to optimise the parameters of the learning-based model to accurately estimate optical flow.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] This process often relies on vast synthetic training datasets, such as FlyingChairs and FlyingThings3D, due to the number of parameters involved.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] The models are then evaluated on benchmarks like MPI Sintel, KITTI, and the high-resolution Spring dataset.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] However, models trained exclusively on synthetic data often struggle with the domain gap when applied to real-world footage.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] To address this, some learning-based optical flow approaches use self-supervised learning (sometimes called unsupervised learning) to reduce the need for large datasets with ground-truth data and leverage real-world footage without labels during training.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Instead of training models to minimise the differences between estimated and ground-truth flow fields, they are trained to achieve learning objectives such as brightness constancy and smoothness of the flow field.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] More recently, methods like CroCo have introduced cross-view completion pre-training.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Forcing the network to predict the masked regions of one image using the full second image teaches the model a strong geometric understanding and better generalization than models trained solely on task-specific labels.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Motion estimation and video compression have developed as a major aspect of optical flow research.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Optical flow was used by robotics researchers in many areas such as: object detection and tracking, image dominant plane extraction, movement detection, robot navigation and visual odometry.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Optical flow information has been recognized as being useful for controlling micro air vehicles.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] The application of optical flow includes the problem of inferring not only the motion of the observer and objects in the scene, but also the structure of objects and the environment.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Since awareness of motion and the generation of mental maps of the structure of our environment are critical components of animal (and human) vision, the conversion of this innate ability to a computer capability is similarly crucial in the field of machine vision.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Consider a five-frame clip of a ball moving from the bottom left of a field of vision, to the top right.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Motion estimation techniques can determine that on a two dimensional plane the ball is moving up and to the right and vectors describing this motion can be extracted from the sequence of frames.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] For the purposes of video compression (e.g., MPEG), the sequence is now described as well as it needs to be.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] However, in the field of machine vision, the question of whether the ball is moving to the right or if the observer is moving to the left is unknowable yet critical information.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Not even if a static, patterned background were present in the five frames, could we confidently state that the ball was moving to the right, because the pattern might have an infinite distance to the observer.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Optical flow has also been applied to fluid mechanics as a method of estimating flow patterns in a non-invasive way if visible tracer particles are added.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] This approach is called particle image velocimetry (PIV).
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] It has been shown that optical flow methods can provide higher accuracy than traditional cross-correlation in PIV processing .
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Various configurations of optical flow sensors exist.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] One configuration is an image sensor chip connected to a processor programmed to run an optical flow algorithm.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Another configuration uses a vision chip, which is an integrated circuit having both the image sensor and the processor on the same die, allowing for a compact implementation.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] An example of this is a generic optical mouse sensor used in an optical mouse.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] In some cases the processing circuitry may be implemented using analog or mixed-signal circuits to enable fast optical flow computation using minimal current consumption.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] One area of contemporary research is the use of neuromorphic engineering techniques to implement circuits that respond to optical flow, and thus may be appropriate for use in an optical flow sensor.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Such circuits may draw inspiration from biological neural circuitry that similarly responds to optical flow.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Optical flow sensors are used extensively in computer optical mice, as the main sensing component for measuring the motion of the mouse across a surface.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Optical flow sensors are also being used in robotics applications, primarily where there is a need to measure visual motion or relative motion between the robot and other objects in the vicinity of the robot.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] The use of optical flow sensors in unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs), for stability and obstacle avoidance, is also an area of current research.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] As early as Euclid's *Optics* note was made of the geometry underlying optic flow.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Helmholtz's nineteenth-century account of motion parallax also implicitly concerns it.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] However, its explicit identification arose during the Second World War due the need to understand how pilots judge height and direction during landing.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] MacCurdy, in advise to the Royal Air Force in the late 1920s, had earlier observed that during a straight descent the point on the ground being approached stays fixed in the pilot's visual field while all other points appear to stream away from it.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Grindley, in a classified 1942 report then mathematically analyzed how retinal velocity changed during self-motion to enable an individual to accurately estimate visual speed.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] He, however, considered only this as a cue to altitude and not information to determine travel.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Army Air Forces, first identified that retinal velocities radiate from a "focus of expansion" in the direction of travel.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Moreover, that eye movements do not disturb this, and that it was the global pattern—not individual velocities—that provided this information.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] In 1947, he published the theory, and in 1950 gave the phenomenon the name "optic flow".
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] In 1955, he together with Paul Olum and Frank Rosenblatt detailed its mathematics.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Calvert at the Royal Aircraft Establishment came to a similar ideas when researching on airport approach lighting.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] In 1949, he proposed them as the "parafoveal streamer theory" which described how pilots use the pattern and speed of visual streamers to control their descent.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Gibson stressed the importance of optic flow for affordance perception, the ability to discern possibilities for action within the environment.
[src:self-driving-perception/optical-flow] Followers of Gibson and his ecological approach to psychology have further demonstrated the role of the optical flow stimulus for the perception of movement by the observer in the world; perception of the shape, distance and movement of objects in the world; and the control of locomotion.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] In digital image processing and computer vision, **image segmentation** is the process of partitioning a digital image into multiple **image segments**, also known as **image regions** or **image objects** (sets of pixels).
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The goal of segmentation is to simplify and/or change the representation of an image into something that is more meaningful and easier to analyze.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Image segmentation is typically used to locate objects and boundaries (lines, curves, etc.) in images.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] More precisely, image segmentation is the process of assigning a label to every pixel in an image such that pixels with the same label share certain characteristics.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The result of image segmentation is a set of segments that collectively cover the entire image, or a set of contours extracted from the image (see edge detection).
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Each of the pixels in a region are similar with respect to some characteristic or computed property, such as color, intensity, or texture.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Adjacent regions are significantly different with respect to the same characteristic(s).
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] When applied to a stack of images, typical in medical imaging, the resulting contours after image segmentation can be used to create 3D reconstructions with the help of geometry reconstruction algorithms like marching cubes.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Several general-purpose algorithms and techniques have been developed for image segmentation.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] To be useful, these techniques must typically be combined with a domain's specific knowledge in order to effectively solve the domain's segmentation problems.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] There are two classes of segmentation techniques.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The simplest method of image segmentation is called the thresholding method.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] This method is based on a clip-level (or a threshold value) to turn a gray-scale image into a binary image.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The key of this method is to select the threshold value (or values when multiple-levels are selected).
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Several popular methods are used in industry including the maximum entropy method, balanced histogram thresholding, Otsu's method (maximum variance), and k-means clustering.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Recently, methods have been developed for thresholding computed tomography (CT) images.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The key idea is that, unlike Otsu's method, the thresholds are derived from the radiographs instead of the (reconstructed) image.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] New methods suggest the use of multi-dimensional, fuzzy rule-based, non-linear thresholds.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] In these approaches, the decision regarding each pixel's membership in a segment is based on multi-dimensional rules derived from fuzzy logic and evolutionary algorithms, considering factors such as image lighting, environment, and application.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Note that a common technique to improve performance for large images is to downsample the image, compute the clusters, and then reassign the values to the larger image if necessary.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The K-means algorithm is an iterative technique that is used to partition an image into *K* clusters.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] In this case, distance is the squared or absolute difference between a pixel and a cluster center.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The difference is typically based on pixel color, intensity, texture, and location, or a weighted combination of these factors.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] *K* can be selected manually, randomly, or by a heuristic.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] This algorithm is guaranteed to converge, but it may not return the optimal solution.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The quality of the solution depends on the initial set of clusters and the value of *K*.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The Mean Shift algorithm is a technique that is used to partition an image into an unknown apriori number of clusters.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] This has the advantage of not having to start with an initial guess of such parameter which makes it a better general solution for more diverse cases.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Motion based segmentation is a technique that relies on motion in the image to perform segmentation.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The idea is simple: look at the differences between a pair of images.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Assuming the object of interest is moving, the difference will be exactly that object.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Improving on this idea, Kenney et al. proposed interactive segmentation .
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] They use a robot to poke objects in order to generate the motion signal necessary for motion-based segmentation.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Interactive segmentation follows the interactive perception framework proposed by Dov Katz and Oliver Brock .
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Another technique that is based on motion is rigid motion segmentation.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Compression based methods postulate that the optimal segmentation is the one that minimizes, over all possible segmentations, the coding length of the data.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The connection between these two concepts is that segmentation tries to find patterns in an image and any regularity in the image can be used to compress it.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The method describes each segment by its texture and boundary shape.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Texture is encoded by lossy compression in a way similar to minimum description length (MDL) principle, but here the length of the data given the model is approximated by the number of samples times the entropy of the model.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The texture in each region is modeled by a multivariate normal distribution whose entropy has a closed form expression.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] An interesting property of this model is that the estimated entropy bounds the true entropy of the data from above.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] This is because among all distributions with a given mean and covariance, normal distribution has the largest entropy.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Thus, the true coding length cannot be more than what the algorithm tries to minimize.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] For any given segmentation of an image, this scheme yields the number of bits required to encode that image based on the given segmentation.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Thus, among all possible segmentations of an image, the goal is to find the segmentation which produces the shortest coding length.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] This can be achieved by a simple agglomerative clustering method.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The distortion in the lossy compression determines the coarseness of the segmentation and its optimal value may differ for each image.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] This parameter can be estimated heuristically from the contrast of textures in an image.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] For example, when the textures in an image are similar, such as in camouflage images, stronger sensitivity and thus lower quantization is required.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Histogram-based methods are very efficient compared to other image segmentation methods because they typically require only one pass through the pixels.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] In this technique, a histogram is computed from all of the pixels in the image, and the peaks and valleys in the histogram are used to locate the clusters in the image.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Color or intensity can be used as the measure.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] A refinement of this technique is to recursively apply the histogram-seeking method to clusters in the image in order to divide them into smaller clusters.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] This operation is repeated with smaller and smaller clusters until no more clusters are formed.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] One disadvantage of the histogram-seeking method is that it may be difficult to identify significant peaks and valleys in the image.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Histogram-based approaches can also be quickly adapted to apply to multiple frames, while maintaining their single pass efficiency.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The histogram can be done in multiple fashions when multiple frames are considered.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The same approach that is taken with one frame can be applied to multiple, and after the results are merged, peaks and valleys that were previously difficult to identify are more likely to be distinguishable.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The histogram can also be applied on a per-pixel basis where the resulting information is used to determine the most frequent color for the pixel location.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] This approach segments based on active objects and a static environment, resulting in a different type of segmentation useful in video tracking.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Edge detection is a well-developed field on its own within image processing.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Region boundaries and edges are closely related, since there is often a sharp adjustment in intensity at the region boundaries.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Edge detection techniques have therefore been used as the base of another segmentation technique.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The edges identified by edge detection are often disconnected.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] To segment an object from an image however, one needs closed region boundaries.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The desired edges are the boundaries between such objects or spatial-taxons.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Spatial-taxons are information granules, consisting of a crisp pixel region, stationed at abstraction levels within a hierarchical nested scene architecture.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] They are similar to the Gestalt psychological designation of figure-ground, but are extended to include foreground, object groups, objects and salient object parts.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Edge detection methods can be applied to the spatial-taxon region, in the same manner they would be applied to a silhouette.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Segmentation methods can also be applied to edges obtained from edge detectors.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The detection of isolated points in an image is a fundamental part of image segmentation.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] This process primarily depends on the second derivative, indicating the use of the Laplacian operator.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The Laplacian operator is employed such that the partial derivatives are derived from a specific equation.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] This mathematical expression can be implemented by convolving with an appropriate mask.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] If we extend this equation to three dimensions (x,y,z), the intensity at each pixel location around a central pixel at (x, y, z) is replaced by their corresponding values.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] This equation becomes particularly useful when we assume that all pixels have unit spacing along each axis.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] A sphere mask has been developed for use with three-dimensional datasets.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The sphere mask is designed to use only integer arithmetic during calculations, thereby eliminating the need for floating-point hardware or software.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] When applying these concepts to actual images represented as arrays of numbers, we need to consider what happens when we reach an edge or border region.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] This above equation is used to determine whether a point in the image is an isolated point based on the response magnitude $|R(x,y)|$ and a threshold value T .
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] If the response magnitude is greater than or equal to the threshold, the function returns 1, indicating the presence of an isolated point; otherwise, it returns 0.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] This helps in the effective detection and segmentation of isolated points in the image.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The detection of isolated points has significant applications in various fields, including X-ray image processing.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] For instance, an original X-ray image of a turbine blade can be examined pixel-by-pixel to detect porosity in the upper-right quadrant of the blade.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The result of applying an edge detector's response to this X-ray image can be approximated.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] This demonstrates the segmentation of isolated points in an image with the aid of single-pixel probes.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] This method is a combination of three characteristics of the image: partition of the image based on histogram analysis is checked by high compactness of the clusters (objects), and high gradients of their borders.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] For that purpose two spaces have to be introduced: one space is the one-dimensional histogram of brightness *H* = *H*(*B*); the second space is the dual 3-dimensional space of the original image itself *B* = *B*(*x*, *y*).
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The first space allows to measure how compactly the brightness of the image is distributed by calculating a minimal clustering kmin.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The bitmap *b* is an object in dual space.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] On that bitmap a measure has to be defined reflecting how compact distributed black (or white) pixels are.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] So, the goal is to find objects with good borders.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] For all *T* the measure *M*DC = *G*/(*k* × *L*) has to be calculated (where *k* is difference in brightness between the object and the background, *L* is length of all borders, and *G* is mean gradient on the borders).
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Maximum of MDC defines the segmentation.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Region-growing methods rely mainly on the assumption that the neighboring pixels within one region have similar values.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The common procedure is to compare one pixel with its neighbors.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] If a similarity criterion is satisfied, the pixel can be set to belong to the same cluster as one or more of its neighbors.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The selection of the similarity criterion is significant and the results are influenced by noise in all instances.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The method of Statistical Region Merging (SRM) starts by building the graph of pixels using 4-connectedness with edges weighted by the absolute value of the intensity difference.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Initially each pixel forms a single pixel region.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] SRM then sorts those edges in a priority queue and decides whether or not to merge the current regions belonging to the edge pixels using a statistical predicate.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] One region-growing method is the seeded region growing method.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] This method takes a set of seeds as input along with the image.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The seeds mark each of the objects to be segmented.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The regions are iteratively grown by comparison of all unallocated neighboring pixels to the regions.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The difference between a pixel's intensity value and the region's mean, $\delta$ , is used as a measure of similarity.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The pixel with the smallest difference measured in this way is assigned to the respective region.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] This process continues until all pixels are assigned to a region.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Because seeded region growing requires seeds as additional input, the segmentation results are dependent on the choice of seeds, and noise in the image can cause the seeds to be poorly placed.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Another region-growing method is the unseeded region growing method.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] It is a modified algorithm that does not require explicit seeds.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] It starts with a single region $A_{1}$ —the pixel chosen here does not markedly influence the final segmentation.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] At each iteration it considers the neighboring pixels in the same way as seeded region growing.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] It differs from seeded region growing in that if the minimum $\delta$ is less than a predefined threshold T then it is added to the respective region $A_{j}$ .
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] If not, then the pixel is considered different from all current regions $A_{i}$ and a new region $A_{n+1}$ is created with this pixel.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] One variant of this technique, proposed by Haralick and Shapiro (1985), is based on pixel intensities.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The mean and scatter of the region and the intensity of the candidate pixel are used to compute a test statistic.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] If the test statistic is sufficiently small, the pixel is added to the region, and the region's mean and scatter are recomputed.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Otherwise, the pixel is rejected, and is used to form a new region.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] A special region-growing method is called $\lambda$ -connected segmentation (see also lambda-connectedness).
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] It is based on pixel intensities and neighborhood-linking paths.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] A degree of connectivity (connectedness) is calculated based on a path that is formed by pixels.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] For a certain value of $\lambda$ , two pixels are called $\lambda$ -connected if there is a path linking those two pixels and the connectedness of this path is at least $\lambda$ . $\lambda$ -connectedness is an equivalence relation.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Split-and-merge segmentation is based on a quadtree partition of an image.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] It is sometimes called quadtree segmentation.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] This method starts at the root of the tree that represents the whole image.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] If it is found non-uniform (not homogeneous), then it is split into four child squares (the splitting process), and so on.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] If, in contrast, four child squares are homogeneous, they are merged as several connected components (the merging process).
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The node in the tree is a segmented node.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] This process continues recursively until no further splits or merges are possible.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] When a special data structure is involved in the implementation of the algorithm of the method, its time complexity can reach $O(n\log n)$ , an optimal algorithm of the method.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Using a partial differential equation (PDE)-based method and solving the PDE equation by a numerical scheme, one can segment the image.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Curve propagation is a popular technique in this category, with numerous applications to object extraction, object tracking, stereo reconstruction, etc.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The central idea is to evolve an initial curve towards the lowest potential of a cost function, where its definition reflects the task to be addressed.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] As for most inverse problems, the minimization of the cost functional is non-trivial and imposes certain smoothness constraints on the solution, which in the present case can be expressed as geometrical constraints on the evolving curve.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Lagrangian techniques are based on parameterizing the contour according to some sampling strategy and then evolving each element according to image and internal terms.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Nowadays, efficient "discretized" formulations have been developed to address these limitations while maintaining high efficiency.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] In both cases, energy minimization is generally conducted using a steepest-gradient descent, whereby derivatives are computed using, e.g., finite differences.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The level-set method was initially proposed to track moving interfaces by Dervieux and Thomasset in 1979 and 1981 and was later reinvented by Osher and Sethian in 1988.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] This has spread across various imaging domains in the late 1990s.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] It can be used to efficiently address the problem of curve/surface/etc. propagation in an implicit manner.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The central idea is to represent the evolving contour using a signed function whose zero corresponds to the actual contour.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Then, according to the motion equation of the contour, one can easily derive a similar flow for the implicit surface that when applied to the zero level will reflect the propagation of the contour.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The level-set method affords numerous advantages: it is implicit, is parameter-free, provides a direct way to estimate the geometric properties of the evolving structure, allows for change of topology, and is intrinsic.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] It can be used to define an optimization framework, as proposed by Zhao, Merriman and Osher in 1996.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] One can conclude that it is a very convenient framework for addressing numerous applications of computer vision and medical image analysis.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Research into various level-set data structures has led to very efficient implementations of this method.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The fast marching method has been used in image segmentation, and this model has been improved (permitting both positive and negative propagation speeds) in an approach called the generalized fast marching method.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The goal of variational methods is to find a segmentation which is optimal with respect to a specific energy functional.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The functionals consist of a data fitting term and a regularizing terms.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] A minimizer $u^{*}$ is a piecewise constant image which has an optimal tradeoff between the squared L2 distance to the given image f and the total length of its jump set.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The jump set of $u^{*}$ defines a segmentation.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The relative weight of the energies is tuned by the parameter $\gamma >0$ .
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The binary variant of the Potts model, i.e., if the range of u is restricted to two values, is often called Chan-Vese model.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The functional value is the sum of the total length of the segmentation curve K , the smoothness of the approximation u , and its distance to the original image f .
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The weight of the smoothness penalty is adjusted by $\mu >0$ .
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The Potts model is often called piecewise constant Mumford-Shah model as it can be seen as the degenerate case $\mu \to \infty$ .
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The optimization problems are known to be NP-hard in general but near-minimizing strategies work well in practice.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Classical algorithms are graduated non-convexity and Ambrosio-Tortorelli approximation.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Graph partitioning methods are an effective tools for image segmentation since they model the impact of pixel neighborhoods on a given cluster of pixels or pixel, under the assumption of homogeneity in images.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] In these methods, the image is modeled as a weighted, undirected graph.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Usually a pixel or a group of pixels are associated with nodes and edge weights define the (dis)similarity between the neighborhood pixels.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The graph (image) is then partitioned according to a criterion designed to model "good" clusters.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Each partition of the nodes (pixels) output from these algorithms are considered an object segment in the image; see Segmentation-based object categorization.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Some popular algorithms of this category are normalized cuts, random walker, minimum cut, isoperimetric partitioning, minimum spanning tree-based segmentation, and segmentation-based object categorization.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The application of Markov random fields (MRF) for images was suggested in early 1984 by Geman and Geman.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Their strong mathematical foundation and ability to provide a global optimum even when defined on local features proved to be the foundation for novel research in the domain of image analysis, de-noising and segmentation.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] MRFs are completely characterized by their prior probability distributions, marginal probability distributions, cliques, smoothing constraint as well as criterion for updating values.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The criterion for image segmentation using MRFs is restated as finding the labelling scheme which has maximum probability for a given set of features.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The broad categories of image segmentation using MRFs are supervised and unsupervised segmentation.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] In terms of image segmentation, the function that MRFs seek to maximize is the probability of identifying a labelling scheme given a particular set of features are detected in the image.
