[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The watershed transformation considers the gradient magnitude of an image as a topographic surface.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Pixels having the highest gradient magnitude intensities (GMIs) correspond to watershed lines, which represent the region boundaries.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Water placed on any pixel enclosed by a common watershed line flows downhill to a common local intensity minimum (LIM).
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Pixels draining to a common minimum form a catch basin, which represents a segment.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The central assumption of model-based approaches is that the structures of interest have a tendency towards a particular shape.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Therefore, one can seek a probabilistic model that characterizes the shape and its variation.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] When segmenting an image, constraints can be imposed using this model as a prior.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Such a task may involve (i) registration of the training examples to a common pose, (ii) probabilistic representation of the variation of the registered samples, and (iii) statistical inference between the model and the image.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Other important methods in the literature for model-based segmentation include active shape models and active appearance models.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Image segmentations are computed at multiple scales in scale space and sometimes propagated from coarse to fine scales; see scale-space segmentation.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Segmentation criteria can be arbitrarily complex and may take into account global as well as local criteria.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] A common requirement is that each region must be connected in some sense.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Witkin's seminal work in scale space included the notion that a one-dimensional signal could be unambiguously segmented into regions, with one scale parameter controlling the scale of segmentation.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] A key observation is that the zero-crossings of the second derivatives (minima and maxima of the first derivative or slope) of multi-scale-smoothed versions of a signal form a nesting tree, which defines hierarchical relations between segments at different scales.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Specifically, slope extrema at coarse scales can be traced back to corresponding features at fine scales.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] When a slope maximum and slope minimum annihilate each other at a larger scale, the three segments that they separated merge into one segment, thus defining the hierarchy of segments.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] There have been numerous research works in this area, out of which a few have now reached a state where they can be applied either with interactive manual intervention (usually with application to medical imaging) or fully automatically.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The following is a brief overview of some of the main research ideas that current approaches are based upon.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The nesting structure that Witkin described is, however, specific for one-dimensional signals and does not trivially transfer to higher-dimensional images.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Nevertheless, this general idea has inspired several other authors to investigate coarse-to-fine schemes for image segmentation.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Koenderink proposed to study how iso-intensity contours evolve over scales and this approach was investigated in more detail by Lifshitz and Pizer.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Unfortunately, however, the intensity of image features changes over scales, which implies that it is hard to trace coarse-scale image features to finer scales using iso-intensity information.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Bergholm proposed to detect edges at coarse scales in scale-space and then trace them back to finer scales with manual choice of both the coarse detection scale and the fine localization scale.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Gauch and Pizer studied the complementary problem of ridges and valleys at multiple scales and developed a tool for interactive image segmentation based on multi-scale watersheds.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The use of multi-scale watershed with application to the gradient map has also been investigated by Olsen and Nielsen and been carried over to clinical use by Dam.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Vincken et al. proposed a hyperstack for defining probabilistic relations between image structures at different scales.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The use of stable image structures over scales has been furthered by Ahuja and his co-workers into a fully automated system.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] A fully automatic brain segmentation algorithm based on closely related ideas of multi-scale watersheds has been presented by Undeman and Lindeberg and been extensively tested in brain databases.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] These ideas for multi-scale image segmentation by linking image structures over scales have also been picked up by Florack and Kuijper.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Bijaoui and Rué associate structures detected in scale-space above a minimum noise threshold into an object tree which spans multiple scales and corresponds to a kind of feature in the original signal.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Extracted features are accurately reconstructed using an iterative conjugate gradient matrix method.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] In one kind of segmentation, the user outlines the region of interest with the mouse clicks and algorithms are applied so that the path that best fits the edge of the image is shown.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Techniques like SIOX, Livewire, Intelligent Scissors or IT-SNAPS are used in this kind of segmentation.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] In an alternative kind of semi-automatic segmentation, the algorithms return a spatial-taxon (i.e. foreground, object-group, object or object-part) selected by the user or designated via prior probabilities.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Most of the aforementioned segmentation methods are based only on color information of pixels in the image.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Humans use much more knowledge when performing image segmentation, but implementing this knowledge would cost considerable human engineering and computational time, and would require a huge domain knowledge database which does not currently exist.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Trainable segmentation methods, such as neural network segmentation, overcome these issues by modeling the domain knowledge from a dataset of labeled pixels.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] An image segmentation neural network can process small areas of an image to extract simple features such as edges.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Another neural network, or any decision-making mechanism, can then combine these features to label the areas of an image accordingly.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] A type of network designed this way is the Kohonen map.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Pulse-coupled neural networks (PCNNs) are neural models proposed by modeling a cat's visual cortex and developed for high-performance biomimetic image processing.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] In 1989, Reinhard Eckhorn introduced a neural model to emulate the mechanism of a cat's visual cortex.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The Eckhorn model provided a simple and effective tool for studying the visual cortex of small mammals, and was soon recognized as having significant application potential in image processing.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] In 1994, the Eckhorn model was adapted to be an image processing algorithm by John L.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Johnson, who termed this algorithm Pulse-Coupled Neural Network.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Over the past decade, PCNNs have been utilized for a variety of image processing applications, including: image segmentation, feature generation, face extraction, motion detection, region growing, noise reduction, and so on.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] A PCNN is a two-dimensional neural network.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Each neuron in the network corresponds to one pixel in an input image, receiving its corresponding pixel's color information (e.g. intensity) as an external stimulus.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Each neuron also connects with its neighboring neurons, receiving local stimuli from them.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The external and local stimuli are combined in an internal activation system, which accumulates the stimuli until it exceeds a dynamic threshold, resulting in a pulse output.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Through iterative computation, PCNN neurons produce temporal series of pulse outputs.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The temporal series of pulse outputs contain information of input images and can be utilized for various image processing applications, such as image segmentation and feature generation.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Compared with conventional image processing means, PCNNs have several significant merits, including robustness against noise, independence of geometric variations in input patterns, capability of bridging minor intensity variations in input patterns, etc.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] In 2015, convolutional neural networks reached state of the art in semantic segmentation.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] U-Net is an architecture which takes as input an image and outputs a label for each pixel.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] U-Net initially was developed to detect cell boundaries in biomedical images.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] U-Net follows classical autoencoder architecture, as such it contains two sub-structures.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The encoder structure follows the traditional stack of convolutional and max pooling layers to increase the receptive field as it goes through the layers.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] It is used to capture the context in the image.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The decoder structure utilizes transposed convolution layers for upsampling so that the end dimensions are close to that of the input image.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Skip connections are placed between convolution and transposed convolution layers of the same shape in order to preserve details that would have been lost otherwise.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Related images such as a photo album or a sequence of video frames often contain semantically similar objects and scenes, therefore it is often beneficial to exploit such correlations.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] The task of simultaneously segmenting scenes from related images or video frames is termed co-segmentation, which is typically used in human action localization.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Unlike conventional bounding box-based object detection, human action localization methods provide finer-grained results, typically per-image segmentation masks delineating the human object of interest and its action category (e.g., *Segment-Tube*).
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] Techniques such as dynamic Markov Networks, CNN and LSTM are often employed to exploit the inter-frame correlations.
[src:self-driving-perception/semantic-segmentation] There are many other methods of segmentation like multispectral segmentation or connectivity-based segmentation based on DTI images.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] SLAM algorithms are tailored to the available resources and are not aimed at perfection but at operational compliance.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Published approaches are employed in self-driving cars, unmanned aerial vehicles, autonomous underwater vehicles, planetary rovers, newer domestic robots and even inside the human body.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Given a series of controls $u_{t}$ and sensor observations $o_{t}$ over discrete time steps t , the SLAM problem is to compute an estimate of the agent's state $x_{t}$ and a map of the environment $m_{t}$ .
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] where Z is the normalization constant, which ensures all the probabilities sum up to 1.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Like many inference problems, the solutions to inferring the two variables together can be found, to a local optimum solution, by alternating updates of the two beliefs in a form of an expectation–maximization algorithm.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Statistical techniques used to approximate the above equations include Kalman filters and particle filters (the algorithm behind Monte Carlo Localization).
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] They provide an estimation of the posterior probability distribution for the pose of the robot and for the parameters of the map.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Methods which conservatively approximate the above model using covariance intersection are able to avoid reliance on statistical independence assumptions to reduce algorithmic complexity for large-scale applications.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Other approximation methods achieve improved computational efficiency by using simple bounded-region representations of uncertainty.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Set-membership techniques are mainly based on interval constraint propagation.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] They provide a set which encloses the pose of the robot and a set approximation of the map.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] MAP estimators compute the most likely explanation of the robot poses and the map given the sensor data, rather than trying to estimate the entire posterior probability.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] New SLAM algorithms remain an active research area, and are often driven by differing requirements and assumptions about the types of maps, sensors and models as detailed below.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Many SLAM systems can be viewed as combinations of choices from each of these aspects.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Topological maps are a method of environment representation which capture the connectivity (i.e., topology) of the environment rather than creating a geometrically accurate map.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Topological SLAM approaches have been used to enforce global consistency in metric SLAM algorithms.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] In contrast, grid maps use arrays (typically square or hexagonal) of discretized cells to represent a topological world, and make inferences about which cells are occupied.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Typically the cells are assumed to be statistically independent to simplify computation.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Under such assumption, $P(m_{t}|x_{t},m_{t-1},o_{t})$ are set to 1 if the new map's cells are consistent with the observation $o_{t}$ at location $x_{t}$ and 0 if inconsistent.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Modern self driving cars mostly simplify the mapping problem to almost nothing, by making extensive use of highly detailed map data collected in advance.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] This can include map annotations to the level of marking locations of individual white line segments and curbs on the road.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Location-tagged visual data such as Google's StreetView may also be used as part of maps.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Essentially such systems simplify the SLAM problem to a simpler localization only task, perhaps allowing for moving objects such as cars and people only to be updated in the map at runtime.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] SLAM will always use several different types of sensors, and the powers and limits of various sensor types have been a major driver of new algorithms.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Statistical independence is the mandatory requirement to cope with metric bias and with noise in measurements.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Different types of sensors give rise to different SLAM algorithms which assumptions are most appropriate to the sensors.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] At one extreme, laser scans or visual features provide details of many points within an area, sometimes rendering SLAM inference unnecessary because shapes in these point clouds can be easily and unambiguously aligned at each step via image registration.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] At the opposite extreme, tactile sensors are extremely sparse as they contain only information about points very close to the agent, so they require strong prior models to compensate in purely tactile SLAM.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Most practical SLAM tasks fall somewhere between these visual and tactile extremes.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Sensor models divide broadly into landmark-based and raw-data approaches.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Landmarks are uniquely identifiable objects in the world which location can be estimated by a sensor, such as Wi-Fi access points or radio beacons.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Raw-data approaches make no assumption that landmarks can be identified, and instead model $P(o_{t}|x_{t})$ directly as a function of the location.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Optical sensors may be one-dimensional (single beam) or 2D- (sweeping) laser rangefinders, 3D high definition light detection and ranging (lidar), 3D flash lidar, 2D or 3D sonar sensors, and one or more 2D cameras.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Since the invention of local features, such as SIFT, there has been intense research into visual SLAM (VSLAM) using primarily visual (camera) sensors, because of the increasing ubiquity of cameras such as those in mobile devices.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Both visual and lidar sensors are informative enough to allow for landmark extraction in many cases.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Other recent forms of SLAM include tactile SLAM (sensing by local touch only), radar SLAM, acoustic SLAM, and Wi-Fi-SLAM (sensing by strengths of nearby Wi-Fi access points).
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Recent approaches apply quasi-optical wireless ranging for multi-lateration (real-time locating system (RTLS)) or multi-angulation in conjunction with SLAM as a tribute to erratic wireless measures.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] A kind of SLAM for human pedestrians uses a shoe mounted inertial measurement unit as the main sensor and relies on the fact that pedestrians are able to avoid walls to automatically build floor plans of buildings by an indoor positioning system.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] For some outdoor applications, the need for SLAM has been almost entirely removed due to high precision differential GPS sensors.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] From a SLAM perspective, these may be viewed as location sensors which likelihoods are so sharp that they completely dominate the inference.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] However, GPS sensors may occasionally decline or go down entirely, e.g. during times of military conflict, which are of particular interest to some robotics applications.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] The $P(x_{t}|x_{t-1})$ term represents the kinematics of the model, which usually include information about action commands given to a robot.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] As a part of the model, the kinematics of the robot is included, to improve estimates of sensing under conditions of inherent and ambient noise.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] The dynamic model balances the contributions from various sensors, various partial error models and finally comprises in a sharp virtual depiction as a map with the location and heading of the robot as some cloud of probability.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Mapping is the final depicting of such model, the map is either such depiction or the abstract term for the model.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] For 2D robots, the kinematics are usually given by a mixture of rotation and "move forward" commands, which are implemented with additional motor noise.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Unfortunately the distribution formed by independent noise in angular and linear directions is non-Gaussian, but is often approximated by a Gaussian.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] An alternative approach is to ignore the kinematic term and read odometry data from robot wheels after each command—such data may then be treated as one of the sensors rather than as kinematics.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Non-static environments, such as those containing other vehicles or pedestrians, continue to present research challenges.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] SLAM with DATMO is a model which tracks moving objects in a similar way to the agent itself.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Loop closure is the problem of recognizing a previously-visited location and updating beliefs accordingly.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] This can be a problem because model or algorithm errors can assign low priors to the location.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Typical loop closure methods apply a second algorithm to compute some type of sensor measure similarity, and reset the location priors when a match is detected.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] For example, this can be done by storing and comparing bag of words vectors of scale-invariant feature transform (SIFT) features from each previously visited location.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] In neuroscience, the hippocampus appears to be involved in SLAM-like computations, giving rise to place cells, and has formed the basis for bio-inspired SLAM systems such as RatSLAM.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] An extension of the common SLAM problem has been applied to the acoustic domain, where environments are represented by the three-dimensional (3D) position of sound sources, termed aSLAM (**A**coustic **S**imultaneous **L**ocalization and **M**apping).
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Early implementations of this technique have used direction-of-arrival (DoA) estimates of the sound source location, and rely on principal techniques of sound localization to determine source locations.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] An observer, or robot must be equipped with a microphone array to enable use of Acoustic SLAM, so that DoA features are properly estimated.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Acoustic SLAM has paved foundations for further studies in acoustic scene mapping, and can play an important role in human-robot interaction through speech.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] To map multiple, and occasionally intermittent sound sources, an acoustic SLAM system uses foundations in random finite set theory to handle the varying presence of acoustic landmarks.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] However, the nature of acoustically derived features leaves Acoustic SLAM susceptible to problems of reverberation, inactivity, and noise within an environment.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Originally designed for human–robot interaction, Audio-Visual SLAM is a framework that provides the fusion of landmark features obtained from both the acoustic and visual modalities within an environment.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Human interaction is characterized by features perceived in not only the visual modality, but the acoustic modality as well; as such, SLAM algorithms for human-centered robots and machines must account for both sets of features.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] An Audio-Visual framework estimates and maps positions of human landmarks through use of visual features like human pose, and audio features like human speech, and fuses the beliefs for a more robust map of the environment.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] For applications in mobile robotics (ex. drones, service robots), it is valuable to use low-power, lightweight equipment such as monocular cameras, or microelectronic microphone arrays.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Audio-Visual SLAM can also allow for complimentary function of such sensors, by compensating the narrow field-of-view, feature occlusions, and optical degradations common to lightweight visual sensors with the full field-of-view, and unobstructed feature representations inherent to audio sensors.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] The susceptibility of audio sensors to reverberation, sound source inactivity, and noise can also be accordingly compensated through fusion of landmark beliefs from the visual modality.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Complimentary function between the audio and visual modalities in an environment can prove valuable for the creation of robotics and machines that fully interact with human speech and human movement.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Various SLAM algorithms are implemented in the open-source software Robot Operating System (ROS) libraries, often used together with the Point Cloud Library for 3D maps or visual features from OpenCV.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] In robotics, *EKF SLAM* is a class of algorithms which uses the extended Kalman filter (EKF) for SLAM.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Typically, EKF SLAM algorithms are feature based, and use the maximum likelihood algorithm for data association.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] In the 1990s and 2000s, EKF SLAM had been the de facto method for SLAM, until the introduction of FastSLAM.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Associated with the EKF is the gaussian noise assumption, which significantly impairs EKF SLAM's ability to deal with uncertainty.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] With greater amount of uncertainty in the posterior, the linearization in the EKF fails.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] In robotics, **GraphSLAM** is a SLAM algorithm which uses sparse information matrices produced by generating a factor graph of observation interdependencies (two observations are related if they contain data about the same landmark).
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] A seminal work in SLAM is the research of Smith and Cheeseman on the representation and estimation of spatial uncertainty in 1986.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Other pioneering work in this field was conducted by the research group of Hugh F.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Durrant-Whyte in the early 1990s. which showed that solutions to SLAM exist in the infinite data limit.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] This finding motivates the search for algorithms which are computationally tractable and approximate the solution.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] The acronym SLAM was coined within the paper, "Localization of Autonomous Guided Vehicles" which first appeared in ISR in 1995.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] The self-driving STANLEY and JUNIOR cars, led by Sebastian Thrun, won the DARPA Grand Challenge and came second in the DARPA Urban Challenge in the 2000s, and included SLAM systems, bringing SLAM to worldwide attention.
[src:self-driving-perception/simultaneous-localization-and-mapping] Mass-market SLAM implementations can now be found in consumer robot vacuum cleaners and virtual reality headsets such as the Meta Quest 2 and PICO 4 for markerless inside-out tracking.
